<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Germany Continues to Lead World in Labor Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The western half of Germany continues
to have the world's most expensive labor costs in 1997, a German
survey showed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by the Cologne-based German Economic
Institute IW put western German labor costs at 47.92 marks (26.62
U.S. dollars) an hour in 1997, about 15 marks (8.3 dollars) more
expensive than the average of all major industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Even eastern Germany had labor costs of 32.97 marks (18.32
dollars) an hour, higher than all the other Group of Seven
industrialized countries except Japan which placed 11th in the
rankings with labor costs of 34.97 marks (19.43 dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which chalked up the world's most expensive
labor costs in the mid-1980s, placed 14th at just 31.83 marks
(17.68 dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
The labor costs of France were estimated at 32.03 marks (17.79
dollars) an hour, Italy 29.96 marks (16.64 dollars), Canada 29.20
marks (16.22 dollars) and Britain 28.62 marks (15.90 dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
