<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Just Peace in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Tuesday stressed that Egypt is keen to bring about a just peace in
the Middle East which realizes the legitimate rights of Arab
people.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the remarks at a meeting with Armed Forces
commanders to mark the 28th anniversary of the Air Defense Forces
Day.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Safwat al-Sherif quoted the president as
saying that Egypt was willing to respect the will of all parties
to reach a suitable decision to realize a just and overall peace.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak added that at the same time, Egypt adhered to Arab
rights and restoration of the legitimate rights of the Palestinian
people so that a just and overall peace could be made.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sherif said Mubarak remained optimistic about realizing
peace in the region despite the "Israeli intransigence, the
absence of credibility as well as reluctance of the major sponsors
of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak is optimistic by nature. He is against
despair," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations have been frozen for
16 months while talks on the Lebanese and Syrian tracks have been
halted since early 1996. The prolonged deadlock has fueled the
speculation that it could lead to violence and confrontation in
the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, viewed as leader in the Arab world, has been playing a
role in advancing the peace process. Only on Sunday, Mubarak held
a three-way summit with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Jordanian King Hussein in Cairo to discuss the peace process and
coordinate their stance toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders called for continued efforts by all sides to
put the derailed peace process back on track and urged Israel to
honor all signed agreements. They warned that the continuation of
the current situation would be very dangerous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
