<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economic Growth Contracts by 12 Pct in 1st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economic growth
contracted by 12.23 percent in the first semester (six months)
this year, the National Bureau of Statistics (BPS) announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia therefore will still face a serious economic
recession in the second semester of this year, BPS chairman Sugito
Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau predicts that overall economic growth this year will
drop by 13.06 percent if no fundamental change in the economic
performance takes place in the second semester, he said.
</P>
<P>
With the national gross domestic product (GDP) estimated to
reach 951.4 trillion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 11,000 rupiah)
this year, he said, Indonesia's GDP per capita would increase from
3.1 million rupiah last year to 4.7 million rupiah this year.
</P>
<P>
The Gross national product (GNP) per capita had also increased
from 3 million rupiah to 4.6 million rupiah. However, he said,
both GDP and GNP were down sharply if they were measured in U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The GDP (per capita) was down from 1,088.7 U.S. dollars to
449.2 U.S. dollars and the GNP (per capita) from 1,055.4 U.S.
dollars to 436.3 U.S. dollars," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the economic crisis started in July last year, the
Indonesian rupiah has lost more than 80 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
