<HEADLINE> N.Irish Fist Minister Warns Peace Process Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's newly-elected
first minister, David Trimble, warned Tuesday that the peace
process was under threat by a three-day-old stand-off between
Protestant Orangemen and security forces over a controversial
parade.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said at a news conference in Belfast, "We all know that
this situation, if it develops badly, has the potential to damage
the entire political process in Northern Ireland. We hope that
this will not happen."
</P>
<P>
He was speaking after a second night of riots across the
province sparked by Orangemen's insistence on marching down a
Catholic road in the town of Portadown, 50 km southwest of
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Three policemen came under gunfire separately early Tuesday
morning in Belfast while patroling in the city. In other cities in
the province, dozens of incidents happened during the night, with
cars being burned and road blocks being erected.
</P>
<P>
"There are considerable dangers here... there is not an
unlimited amount of time and I do think it necessary for all
sections of the community here to rally round," said Trimble.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British army said it was sending an extra 800
troops to Northern Ireland in addition to the 17,000 already
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
