<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Meet to Strengthen Int'l Control of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Experts from over 100 countries
began here Tuesday a three-day meeting to discuss how to
strengthen international controls of ozone-depleting substances
like CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons).
</P>
<P>
Participants will try to find ways to improve the effectiveness
of the Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone
Layer, said the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss how to make a new licensing system for
controlling trade in CFCs and other ozone-depleting substances
operational by the year 2000, the UNEP said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed system, governments must issue licenses for
each import and export and inform other governments. This will
enable customs and police officials to track trade in CFCs and
detect illegal trade.
</P>
<P>
Another issue on the Open-ended Working Group's agenda is
whether or not to accept a number of applications for
"essential-use exemptions" that would allow certain developed
countries to use small quantities of particular chemicals for
medical and other special purposes in the years 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
A related matter is how to phase out the use in developing
countries of CFCs in metered-dose inhalers, which are vitally
important to many people suffering from asthma.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also evaluate the progress being made in
adopting ozone-friendly replacements for those substances and
applications where single alternatives to ozone-depleting
substances have not yet been found.
</P>
<P>
These include aerosols, solvents, carbon tetrachloride,
sterilants, rigid and flexible foams, halons, methyl bromide,
refrigeration, air conditioning, heat pumps, and the use of
ozone-depleting substances in military installations.
</P>
<P>
The ozone layer is a protective fragile shield of gas that
absorbs harmful ultraviolet rays of the sun but has been
increasingly pierced by holes caused by manmade chemicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
