<HEADLINE> France Denies Report on Recognition of Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The French government denied a report
on Tuesday that it is preparing to recognize a Palestinian state
as soon as it is founded.
</P>
<P>
"All that contains nothing new, and there is no change in the
stand of France, which is also that of its partners within the
European Union," said Foreign Ministry assistant spokesman Yves
Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli newspaper Haaretz said on Tuesday that France will
recognize Palestine as soon as it declares independence after its
interim period of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
It said that the decision was made by the highest French
leaders including President Jacques Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin and Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a Palestinian state was on the agenda for
negotiations on the final status of the Palestinian territory, as
stated in the peace agreements signed in Oslo between Palestine
and Israel, said Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Doutriaux said that France wished that the Middle East peace
process was relaunched.
</P>
<P>
He described France's unilateral recognition of a Palestinian
state as a hypothetical question.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 15 European Union (EU) states at a summit last
month in Cardiff, Wales, asked Israel to recognize the rights of
the Palestinians and give them the right to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
And they did not rule out the possible creation of a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac said in the spring of 1996 that the
Palestinians had legitimate aspirations for an independent state.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat repeatedly said that the
Palestinians would establish an independent state as soon as the
transitional autonomous period expired in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has firmly rejected
such a possibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
