<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Attractive for Foreign Investors: Lloyds Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- International investors prepared to
take a long-term view of the Asian economic situation could
prosper from the market as it struggles to recover, Lloyds Bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Although Asian economies will go through a further lean period
-- restructuring inefficient financial systems and resolving
indebtedness -- the long-term outlook is promising, the bank said
in its latest Economic Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Foley, chief economist of the bank, said, "Asia's
long-term prospects still compare favorably with the rest of the
world."
</P>
<P>
"The huge decline in the stock market and other asset prices
means that Asia businesses now look extremely attractive as
targets for direct foreign investment, especially in countries
where exchange rates have also fallen," he added.
</P>
<P>
Looking at the recent crisis, Lloyds Bank said the UK had been
far less affected than previously believed. Because of limited
dependence on Asian trade, just 0.2 percent had been knocked off
gross domestic product this year by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fears that the UK could be flooded by cheaper high quality
imports have also been unwarranted as Asian manufacturers have
been unable to raise capital to export, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank believed that there might be long-term UK
implications from the crisis fueled principally by U.S. monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve, which sets interest rates, last week
decided to leave them unchanged as the pace of economic growth
slows.
</P>
<P>
Lloyds Bank said that one of the first casualties was the
manufacturing sector which declined for the first time in two
years, partly driven by the crisis in Asia, with whom the U.S.
trades extensively.
</P>
<P>
Foley said, "Should the U.S. raise rates, it will need to take
into account not only the direct impact on the U.S. economy but
also the indirect effect throughout the rest of the world."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
