<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Urged to Probe Gulf War Syndrome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Gulf War veterans Tuesday
appealed to the British government to stage a public inquiry into
the Gulf War syndrome.
</P>
<P>
A group of British Gulf War veterans and their family members
Tuesday delivered a strong petition bearing thousands of
signatures to British Prime Minister Tony Blair, demanding an
immediate public inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Tony Flint, spokesman for the National Gulf Veterans and
Families Association, told reporters, "With a public inquiry we
will be able to get behind some of the lies and cover-ups that
have been going on for the last seven years."
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for British veterans insist that a cocktail of
immunizations to protect them against chemical and biological
warfare was the likely cause of the mysterious disease.
</P>
<P>
"The cocktail of vaccinations we were given had never been
tested before. We were guinea pigs," Flint said.
</P>
<P>
Flint noted that among the 51,000 British troops who served in
the Gulf War, 6,000 veterans were now ill and some 250 of them
have so far died from Gulf War illnesses.
</P>
<P>
However, British Ministry of Defense officials said Tuesday
that while the government was committed to addressing Gulf War
veterans' concerns "openly, sympathetically and seriously," there
was no need to open a public inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Last July, Britain's Armed Forces Minister John Reed launched a
program on offering medical advice to Gulf War veterans and making
research into the Gulf War Syndrome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
