<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese NPC Chairman Looks Into Rural Democratic Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIPING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
Committee of China's National People's Congress, visited a village
near the city of Siping in Jilin Province today to discuss with
local farmers the way of electing village committees.
</P>
<P>
This morning, he went to the village of Huojiadian, with a
population of 2,945, where four village committee elections have
been held since 1988 in accordance with the Organic Village
Committee Law.
</P>
<P>
After visiting two rural families in Huojiadian and watching
videotapes of the village elections, Li discussed the Organic
Village Committee Law and an amendment to it with villagers.
</P>
<P>
Han Xingfu, the head of the village committee, told Li that
villagers' awareness of democracy and participation have gradually
increased after the elections and that the election process has
become more standardized and is on a better legal footing.
</P>
<P>
Li took note of the man's words and asked questions frequently,
showing great concern for the village election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese NPC Chairman Looks Into Rural Democratic Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the discussion, Li Peng brought up three important
issues.
</P>
<P>
First, in amending the Village Committee Law, villagers'
democratic rights need to be guaranteed so that they can elect
someone they really trust.
</P>
<P>
Second, the representative meeting, which is not specifically
mentioned in the Village Committee Law, but which has proven to be
a convenient means of voicing villagers' opinions, especially in
large villages, needs to be maintained and even improved.
</P>
<P>
Third, village affairs, especially those that directly involve
villagers' interests, need to be kept open so that villagers can
keep a close watch on village affairs.
</P>
<P>
In concluding, Li emphasized that one favorable way to help
China's farmers become better-off is to maintain democracy and
rule of law in China's immense countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
