<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges Ethiopia, Eritrea to Seek Ground of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday called on Ethiopia and
Eritrea to seek a ground of understanding and solve their
territorial dispute through political means.
</P>
<P>
"The situation remains very worrying and we hope that the two
protagonists could show proof of all possible restraint to avoid
the worse," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He said that France hopes that both Ethiopia and Eritrea have a
political will to solve their problems.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin is on a visit in Paris
within a Europe tour, which has already brought him to London and
Bonn, to "explain the Ethiopian position" in the conflict between
Addis Abeba and Asmara.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Mesfin Tuesday, French State Secretary in
charge of relations with Africa Charles Josselin said that the two
countries have all the means to solve the problems which come down
from the independence of Eritrea in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Josselin said that France supports all mediation efforts aimed
at creating an atmosphere of confidence, especially those by the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
An Eritrean envoy visited France last week also to explain the
position of his government in this conflict.
</P>
<P>
The French spokesman also said that France is ready to offer
diplomatic support to the mediations.
</P>
<P>
France helped solve a territorial dispute between Ethiopia and
Yemen in the Red Sea two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea were plunged into an undeclared war on May
6 because of a territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have massed troops on their common border and
the situation remains highly tense although fighting nominally
stopped on June 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
