<HEADLINE> VW Sets Up Private Fund to Compensate Wartime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest carmaker Volkswagen
AG said Tuesday that it will set up a private fund to compensate
forced laborers employed by the company during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The company said in a press release issued Tuesday that the
private fund would be used to provide "humanitarian help" to
individual victims who were forced to work in the wartime
Volkswagen factory in the German city of Wolfsburg during the
period from 1944 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
According to an independent survey quoted by German press
reports, about two thirds of Volkswagen employees during World War
II were forced laborers, including over 1,500 Jewish workers
during the last two years of the war.
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen has previously refused to offer direct compensations
to those people. The last move is said to be prompted by a lawsuit
being prepared by 30 former Jewish workers who want to seek
compensations from Volkswagen for their unpaid wages for the
wartime jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
