<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Reports Steep Drop in Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's unemployment dropped by
seasonally adjusted 122,300 to 4.075 million in June, the sharpest
decline for the month since the 1990 German reunification, the
German Federal Labor Office announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate, measured on the basis of
seasonally unadjusted data, fell to 10.5 percent from 10.9 percent
registered in May, the latest jobless data released by the office
showed.
</P>
<P>
In western Germany, the number of people out of work fell by
51,900 to a jobless rate of 8.9 percent, and the eastern German
jobless total fell by 70,400 to a rate of 17.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the June data, German government spokesman Otto Hauser
said that with the economic upswing strengthening in Germany, an
overall trend reversal on the job market had finally been achieved
after years of adverse developments.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the latest positive development should be
attributable partly to the economic reforms introduced by
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government over the past years.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition politicians and trade unionists argued that
the positive June data had been artificially boosted by government
job-creation programs ahead of the country's general elections on
September 27 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
