<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, U.S. to Open Strategic Dialog in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
will travel to Washington Friday to open the Egyptian-American
strategic dialog, which was designed to speed up coordination
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Moussa met here Tuesday with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's envoy, Greg Craig, who is visiting Egypt to place the
final touches on the upcoming Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Daniel Kurtzer, who attended the
meeting, said that although Egypt and the U.S. have always been
engaged in a dialog, this new dialog would enable the sides to
hold at least one ministerial meeting and periodical meetings on
lower levels every year.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomat told reporters that the aim of this
dialog was to create a fast communication channel between the
U.S. State Department and the Egyptian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"It will enable each side to better understand the demands of
the other end to overcome any type of misunderstandings that
might arise and coordinate stances when required," he said.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the upcoming talks will be the stalled
Middle East peace process and the Israeli refusal to accept the
U.S. proposal for a 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank. At the same time, bilateral economic cooperation will also
take a prominent place.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Egyptian Minister of Economy Youssef Boutros
Ghali discussed with Kurtzer a draft trade cooperation framework
to be submitted to an upcoming meeting of the Egyptian-American
Presidential Council, co-chaired by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and American Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which is similar to the accords already struck
by the U.S. with Chile and Mexico, will provide a necessary
framework regulating the Egyptian-American trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Ghali said such agreement would be a step forward in concluding
a free trade accord between the two sides. During a visit to the
U.S. later last month, he already discussed with U.S. officials on
ways of increasing bilateral trade and upgrading economic ties.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed how to use the U.S. economic aid to Egypt
to serve the country's new needs of transforming its economy into
a market economy. The U.S. Congress is considering cutting this
aid according to its policy of reducing foreign economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, as the first Arab country to seal peace with Israel,
gets a total of 815 million U.S. dollars of U.S. economic aid
every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
