<HEADLINE> 830 Hutu Youths Give Up to Rwandan Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 830 Hutu youths are
said to have surrendered to the Rwandan army in northwestern
Rwanda, Gisenyi prefecture officials told Rwanda News Agency
(RNA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials confirmed a state-run radio Rwanda report that
had earlier indicated that for a period of a month, 803 Hutu
militia youths, girls and boys had handed themselves over to
government officials in Ngororero sous-prefecture, south of
Gisenyi town.
</P>
<P>
Thirty others had reportedly gave themselves up in Karago and
Giciye, formerly home to late president Juvenal Habyarimana.
</P>
<P>
The youths are said to have helped the army to retrieve some
military equipment, including assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
''Some of these young people started training while in refugee
camps in former Zaire,'' the official in charge of administrative
and political affairs in Gisenyi, Gerard Ngoga told RNA.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngoga, the Gisenyi District officials are busy
trying to re-educate the young people through public debates
where issues of national unity and reconciliation are leading
themes, RNA said, in a dispatch to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
''We also plan to organize a solidarity camp like other
returnees to enable them to be integrated in society,'' Ngoga was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The region of Ngororero borders the southern edge of Gisenyi
and Ruhengeri, seen as fertile grounds of Hutu extremists largely
blamed for the violence rocking parts of northwestern Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
For the months of April and May, about 100,000 Hutu civilians
had dissociated themselves with Hutu extremists in northwestern
Rwanda and returned to normal life in villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
