<HEADLINE> Greece Criticizes Turkish Demand for Aegean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday criticized a Turkish
demand for the demilitarization of Aegean islands.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas dismissed the Turkish demand as "historically
unacceptable and groundless," saying that Turkey's such move
undermined the relations between the two countries and did not
contribute to peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish demand contained in a document which was handed to
Greece's ambassador to Turkey Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had not honored commitments undertaken in the past, he
said, adding that Greece could not remain indifferent and had no
choice but to organize its defense.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have been at odds for decades over their
disputes in the territorial waters, air space limits, the
delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the
protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, Turkey has questioned the Greek sovereignty
of several uninhabited islands in the Aegean, but Greece has
rejected Turkey's demand.
</P>
<P>
Greece insists that it has no problems with Turkey in the
Aegean except the continental shelf issue, and if Turkey intends
to question Greece's sovereignty over the Aegean islands, Turkey
will have to go to the international court at the Hague for
arbitration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
