<HEADLINE> 39 Percent of Frenchmen Declare Themselves Leftwing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-nine percent of Frenchmen and
Frenchwomen say they are more or less leftwing, as compared with
31 percent who claim to be rightwing, according to a poll
published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which was conducted by the SOFRES polling group from
June 23 to 26 among 1,000 people representative of the French
population, shows that more men support leftwing parties than
women, and more young people favor the ideas of the leftwing than
the aged.
</P>
<P>
The poll also shows that the Green Party's support rate is
rising, while the Gaullist RPR is losing its partisan basis.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, 62 percent of French people hold a
positive opinion about the Green Party, 55 percent support the
Socialist Party, and 43 percent support the RPR.
</P>
<P>
It also shows that 74 percent of French people support free
trade, 67 percent support competition, 55 support economic
liberalism, 55 support labor unions, 51 percent support
privatization of state enterprises and 50 percent support
socialism.
</P>
<P>
Around half of the people polled say they don't agree to such
ideas as profits, nationalization of enterprises, protectionism,
capitalism and leadership.
</P>
<P>
SOFRES said the poll shows that more and more French people are
accepting the ideas of market, competition, free trade,
modernization and opening, while both rightwing and leftwing
conservatives are losing support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
