<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti PM Cautions Against Offending Arab Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Prime Minister Crown
Prince Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah Tuesday urged
lawmakers to refrain from openly criticizing Arab leaders,
regardless of their positions on Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah issued the appeal during the National Assembly's
discussion on the annual budget of the Kuwait Fund for Arab
Economic Development (KFAED), the official news agency Kuna
reported.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on statements made by parliament member
Mosalam Al-Barak, who criticized King Hussein of Jordan for
supporting Iraq during the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Al-Barak claimed that the motive for Hussein's current moves to
mend fences with Kuwait were aimed at obtaining loans from the
KFAED. He said the KFAED should change its loan policy following
the 1990 Iraqi aggression against Kuwait and stop assistance to
countries that sided with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In response, Al-Sabah urged all lawmakers to "carefully select
their words so that they do not offend any Arab or foreign
figure," regardless of their previous or current positions toward
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made it clear that he, like any other
Kuwaiti citizens, was also angry at Jordan's silence before the
1990 Iraqi aggression and its position during the aggression.
</P>
<P>
He added that if any lawmaker had any objection to the
allocation of the KFAED funds, then it could call for amending the
budget without offending foreign figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
