<HEADLINE> Germany Urges Ethiopia, Eritrea to Renounce Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
Tuesday called on Ethiopia and Eritrea to renounce the use of
force in solving their border dispute.
</P>
<P>
"Violence is not a permissible means of politics. Neither
Ethiopia nor Eritrea, two of the poorest countries in the world,
can afford to solve their border conflict through military means,"
said Kinkel during a meeting with Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin in Bonn Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mesfin is currently on a Europe tour to explain the Ethiopian
position in the conflict between Addis Abeba and Asmara.
</P>
<P>
According to a German Foreign Ministry spokesman, Kinkel called
on both countries to reach a formal truce immediately and stop any
forms of war preparations on their border.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister also expressed full support for the
mediation efforts made by the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
in order to seek a peaceful solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the German Ministry for Economic Cooperation
and Development said that existing German development aid to
Ethiopia would remain in place, but new aid would only be granted
after the end of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea were plunged into an undeclared war on May
6 due to the border dispute. Both sides have massed troops on
their common border and the situation remains highly tense
although fighting nominally stopped on June 11. 
</P>
