<HEADLINE> Rwandan Ex-soldiers on Reeducation Courses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The former soldiers of the Rwandan
government army are pursuing their reeducation courses designed
for their reintegration in normal life.
</P>
<P>
"Before the end of the year, all former Rwandan government
forces (ex-FAR) will have terminated these courses," the Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) Tuesday quoted Second-Lieutenant Jean Claude
Bizimana as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bizimana is in charge of the reeducation program.
</P>
<P>
The latest group of ex-FAR to end such reeducation courses
consists of 860 soldiers from southwestern Cyangugu Prefecture,
RNA said in a dispatch to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
While addressing these soldiers Monday, Rwandan Minister of
Justice Faustin Nteziryayo reminded the ex-FAR soldiers of the
obligation they have to associate with other citizens in
safeguarding security.
</P>
<P>
Nteziryayo also promised that some will be reintegrated in the
army while others will be helped to enter ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
According to Bizimana, more than 6,700 ex-FAR soldiers have
undergone such reeducation courses in six prefectures of the
war-torn country. 
