<HEADLINE> Sudan Government Contacts with Rebels: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Sudanese official has
confirmed that contacts were underway between the government and
the Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA), led by John Garang,
on the possibility of ending the bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old civil war between government troops and the
Garang movement, the major rebel group in the south of the
country, has led to heavy human and material losses.
</P>
<P>
In a press release broadcast Tuesday by the Sudan radio, Riyak
Mashar, chief of the Coordination Council of the Southern
Provinces, said that several delegations have been sent to Garang
and some faction leaders supporting him, to narrow the gap and
pave the way for a solution during the upcoming round of talks in
August in Adis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The contacts have achieved positive results, Mashar said,
emphasizing the necessity of continuing this effort to bring the
two sides closer.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out Garang's involvement in the recent bombing attacks
that took place on June 29 and 30 in capital Khartoum. The attacks
were aborted by the Sudanese security organs.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that it was not in Garang's interest to
topple the incumbent regime in Sudan, and asserted that "Garang
would take the peace track."
</P>
<P>
The rulers and governments of the southern provinces were
instructed to go immediately to their posts and assume duties,
Mashar noted.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation work in the southern provinces have started,
he said, adding that members of his mission would head within days
for the south to inspect the progress by themselves.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Othman Ibrahim Al-Tawil, member of the coordination
council, has complained about the displacement, homelessness,
famine and diseases in the 10 southern provinces.
</P>
<P>
He said it was a transitional period and that the council was
moving slowly. He added that the monthly financing of the Ministry
of Finance was that "We spend out of what we collect" and this
explained why the council is facing a financial deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
