<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asylum-Seeking Pakistani, Fraud: U.S. Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists and
administration officials have found that a Pakistani man's
allegation about Pakistan's planned preemptive nuclear attack on
India was inconceivable and he is a fraud, according to Tuesday's
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Frank von Hippel, chairman of the research arm of the
anti-nuclear weapon Federation of American Scientists, said he and
several Princeton University associates reached their conclusion
after interviewing Iftikhar Khan Chaudry for an hour.
</P>
<P>
Chaudry fled his motherland last month and came to the United
States asking for political asylum by offering what he alleged
Pakistan's planned nuclear strike on India.
</P>
<P>
He has been interviewed thereupon by the FBI in relation to his
claims, but the bureau has not commented publicly on the case.
</P>
<P>
However, Hippel has now made it public after his interview with
Chaudry, saying "everything was wrong."
</P>
<P>
"He doesn't know the most elementary facts about what a nuclear
reactor is," he said. "Our guess is he doesn't have more than a
high school education." It contradicts Chaudry's claim that he has
a graduate education.
</P>
<P>
A senior administration official who has reviewed government
agencies' reports about Chaudry's claims said he is "an absolute
fraud."
</P>
<P>
Pakistani officials have asserted that Chaudry is not a nuclear
physicist, but an accountant at a firm that manufactures bathroom
tiles.
</P>
<P>
Chaudry's father also disavowed his son's story, saying he has
studied business and was not a scientist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
