<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Defense Minister Leaves for Russian Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister Yiannakis
Omirou left here Tuesday for a four-day visit to Russia, during
which he will discuss bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at Larnaca International Airport before
his departure for Moscow, Omirou said he would discuss with his
Russian counterpart Igor Sergeyev in Moscow the implementation of
the 1996 defense cooperation agreeement as well as the Cyprus
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that although Cyprus and Russia differed
greatly in size, they enjoyed ties of friendship based on the
principles of international laws. He said both countries were
interested in consolidating peace, stability and cooperation in
the Mediterranean region and rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Omirou noted that at the present time it was particularly
useful to have this exchange of views in order to support efforts
aimed at achieving a just and viable solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops took over the northern
third in the aftermath of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Omirou's trip will be followed by a visit by President Glafcos
Clerides between July 11-14, at the invitation of Moscow Mayor
Yuri Ruskov as a guest of honor at the World Youth Games. Clerides
will also meet Russian President Boris Yeltsin during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the two Cypriot leaders' Moscow visit is
the deployment of the Russian-made S-300 ani-aircraft missiles,
which are scheduled to be delivered next month.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the Russian missiles in 1997 in
a bid to boost its air defense, but the deal has triggered
warnings from rival Turkish Cypriots and their powerful ally
Turkey, which threatened to take "all necessary measures" to
prevent the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has declared that the missile deal could
be cancelled only if progress is achieved in reaching a peaceful
settlement, for example, the realization of the island's
demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
The position was echoed by Russian Foreign Ministry official
Valery Nesterushkin, who said earlier this week that Moscow could
scrap the delivery of the S-300s "if efforts aimed at studying a
demilitarized status for the island become reality."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that if there was no progress in getting
the two sides to reach an agreement, then the delivery of the
missiles would be go ahead as planned.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Turkish Cypriots and Greek Cypriots
have broken down since last Summer when Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash walked out the talks to protest against European
Union's intention to open accession talks with the Cypriot
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
