<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Ways to Resolve Problems Facing Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to the
United Nations Qin Huasun suggested ways to resolve the problems
facing the developing countries in market access at the annual
session of the Economic and Social Council which opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the goals of economic development of the developing
countries and the need for gradual opening of their markets
consistent with such goals should be fully respected.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries shall not insist on opening their markets
without taking full consideration of the level and stage of
development of the developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the developed countries must scrupulously honor their
commitments to improve market access for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
He said they should stick to their commitments to eliminate
tariff peaks made in the Uruguay Round, reduce non-tariff
barriers, cease the abusive use of anti-dumping measures, provide
more market access opportunities for the goods and services of the
developing countries and improve the external economic environment
for the developing countries to enable them to derive greater
globalization and liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the World Trade Organization should at this
stage concentrate its efforts on the implementation of the Uruguay
Round Agreements instead of diverting its attention to new issues
that have little to do with market access.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries must strengthen their coordination and
enhance their capacity for participating in the multilateral
trading system, Qin added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
