<HEADLINE> Iranians to Start Pilgrimage to Iraq in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said on Tuesday that Tehran is soon to start sending
pilgrims to visit the Shiite holy sites in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between the two neighbors in April,
Kharrazi said, the first group of 3,000 people are to leave for
the holy sites in August.
</P>
<P>
He said that details on the pilgrimage would be announced later
by the Islamic Revolution's Martyrs Foundation and related
officials.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-Iraq agreement allows 3,000 Iranian pilgrims each week
to visit southern Iraq, including Najaf and Karbala, where Shiite
holy shrines are located, as a step toward normalization of
relations between the two former enemies.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Baghdad made a tentative move by allowing a smaller
number of Iranian pilgrims to the south to pay heir homage.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian delegation visited Baghdad last month, and reached
an agreement with Iraqi side to close the files of prisoner of
wars (POW) left over from their bloody war from 1980-88.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 5,584 Iraqi POWs were swapped for 319 Iranians in
April. In early June, the two sides exchanged the remains of some
200 soldiers killed in the war. 
</P>
