<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Qin Comments on Uruguay Round Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The conclusion of the
Uruguay Round Agreements has significantly reduced tariff and
non-tariff barriers and strengthened the multilateral trading
system, the Chinese representative said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It has also greatly fostered the liberalization of global trade
and provided opportunities for greater participation by the
developing countries in international trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual session of the Economic and Social
Council which opened Monday, Qin Huasun, Chinese ambassador to the
United Nations, said, "However, we have to bear in mind that the
results of the Uruguay Round Agreements are by no means balanced."
</P>
<P>
Qin said those who benefit most from those agreements are the
developed countries, and on the other hand, the needs and
interests of the developing countries have not been fully
accommodated and those of the least developed countries have been
largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the implementation of the Uruguay Round Agreements
related to market access has encountered a series of problems
including:
</P>
<P>
-- The developed countries spare no efforts in implementing
those agreements which are in their best interest, but are
unwilling to facilitate the implementation of those agreements
which benefit the developing countries most;
</P>
<P>
-- The developed countries have not loosened their grip on
multilateral policy-making, They arbitrarily expand the scope of
the coordination of the World Trade Organization to include
questions extraneous to market access in the multilateral trading
system. Some countries, in a self-serving manner, selectively
expand new areas of trade, liberalization without regard to the
present level of development of many developing countries, to the
detriment of the latter's economic development;
</P>
<P>
-- The developing countries are still facing many obstacles in
market access. Tariff peaks and tariff escalation in some sectors
in the developed markets are seriously hampering the exports from
developing countries. Moreover, new forms of trade protectionism
risk to further erode the export interests of the developing
countries;
</P>
<P>
-- The present multilateral trading system is increasingly
demanding full reciprocity from developing countries and is thus
undermining the principle of special and different treatment for
developing countries;
</P>
<P>
-- The admission of new members has been delayed by political
considerations and tactics for reaping maximum economic benefits.
Some accession negotiations have become all-encompassing reviews
of the applicants' economic and trade policies. Some members have
been relying on the accession negotiations as the most convenient
venue for resolving bilateral trade problems, thus prolongs the
process of accession negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
