<HEADLINE> Cyprus Government Ready to Restart Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Responding to an appeal by the
U.N. Security Council, Cyprus government Tuesday said it was ready
to restart direct talks with Turkish Cypriots to end the disputes
between them.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides told reporters Tuesday that
"President Glafcos Clerides is ready to return to the negotiating
table even tomorrow with a view to find a solution of the Cyprus
question."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council urged Turkish and Greek Cypriots to
resume direct talks after heard a report by U.N. envoy for Cyprus
Diego Cordovez Monday, who met Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash separately last week.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez said Saturday in Nicosia that he has found "the two
sides interested in trying to find a way to resume the talks," and
he has made progress in the effort to reach a new formula for
negotiations acceptable to both sides.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate, but said this was his first part of a
"two-phase mission to touch base with both leaders to see whether
they were ready to resume direct talks," and he would return to
Cyprus in September.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides said at his daily
press briefing Tuesday that the new U.N. appeal proves "the
Council's resolve to break the deadlock and overcome the impasse
in the Cyprus problem," and its "political will to exert pressure
on the Turkish side to enter into a substantive dialog."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace negotiations have been stalled since last July
when Denktash walked out of the talks to protest against a
decision by the European Union (EU) to start accession talks with
Greek Cypriot-led government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has demanded recognition for his self-declared
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in the northern part of the
island and Cyprus' withdrawal of its application for the EU
membership before restarting the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
landed troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the island
through a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation, but so far little
progress has been made in this direction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
