<HEADLINE> Egypt to Export 37 Million Dollar Food to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will export 37 million
U.S. dollars worth of food to Iraq next week as part of the United
Nations oil-for-food program, the Middle East News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The food, including some 36,000 tonnes of margarine and 2,000
tonnes of cheese, would be exported by Egyptian state-owned
companies affiliated to the Holding Company for Foodstuffs
Industries, said company head Adel al Shahawi, who returned here
from Iraqi capital Baghdad Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Shahawi signed during his visit a number of agreements on
exporting Egyptian products to Baghdad under the
Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Iraq has agreed to import 150 million dollars
worth of foodstuffs from Egypt in the later half of this year and
to increase its food import from Egypt by 250 million dollars next
year.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program signed in 1996, Iraq
is permitted to sell a limited amount of oil every six months to
import food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
that the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In addition to exporting food and medicines to Iraq, Egyptian
companies are also keen to participating in the projects of
renovating Iraq's dilapidated oil facilities and prospecting for
new oil fields. 
</P>
