<HEADLINE> Rubin Says Japan's Economy in Morass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin Tuesday described the Japanese economy as being struck in a
morass.
</P>
<P>
"Among the various things Japan needs to do is a sufficient
fiscal program so it can help them get out of the morass that
they've been in," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
His blunt comment came after Japanese ministers reiterated
their promises to overhaul the country's tax code, including a
possibility of tax cut. But no details of the plan have emerged.
</P>
<P>
Japan's maximum combined rate for national and local income
taxes is among the highest in the world and is viewed as a key
reason for a slump in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Tax cuts and reforms to overhaul Japan's debt-burdened banking
system is at the top of a wish list that Washington has repeatedly
submitted to Tokyo, so far without much apparent success.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the key for Japan to revitalize its economy now in
recession is to "have a strong and sustained fiscal stimulus,"
which he said should be Japan's objective.
</P>
<P>
Japan is viewed by the United States as the cornerstone to
defuse Asia's economic crisis, and is under increasing presure
from the international community to live up to its role as the
region's economic powerhouse. But Japanese leaders seem reluctant
to promise major reforms ahead of the July 12 Upper House of
parliamentary election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
