<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Works with Nile Basin States in Water Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said Tuesday that is closely
cooperating with Nile Basin countries in making optimal use of
an estimated 1,600 billion cubic meters of Nile water each year.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported that Minister of Public
Works and Water Resources Mahmoud Abud Zeid made the statement
when addressing the inaugural meeting of a three-day symposium on
Egypt's water resources and its developments.
</P>
<P>
He said a meeting of water resources ministers of the littoral
countries on the Nile will be held in Cairo in September to
discuss ways of optimizing the use of the longest river in Africa
and carry out joint projects benifiting from the Nile water.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is developing major national projects such as the Toshka
land reclamation project and Al Salam Canal, which depend solely
on Egypt's quota of 55.5 billion cubic meters without any new
additions, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture consumes about 85 percent of Egypt's Nile water
quota while the remainder is used for drinking and navigation.
</P>
<P>
Zeid said that Egypt's policy is to provide irrigation water
for new projects, through recycling agricultural drainage water
which is estimated at 1 billion cubic meters annually, in addition
to subterranean water in the Delta and the Nile Valley which
exceeds 4.7 billion cubic meters annually.
</P>
<P>
"There are no problems whatsoever among Nile basin countries,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Nile basin countries, which groups Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania,
Uganda, Rwanda, Eritrea, Burundi, Kenya, Zaire and Ethiopia, hold
a conference very year during which the water problems are
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
There have been some differences among the Nile littoral
countries over the development projects launched on the river,
with some claiming that these water projects have infringed on the
others' rights.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, accused of trespassing others' share by its recent
construction of the mega project of New Valley, rejected the
charge and urged the basin countries to launch joint ventures to
their common good, instead of evolving a new Nile agreement.
</P>
<P>
The countries overlooking the Nile are bounded by an agreement
signed in 1959 as regards how much water they are entitled to but
some are asking to amend it.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Egypt has access to 55.5 billion cubic
meters, which accounts for 99 percent of its sweet water resources.
</P>
<P>
The 6,700-kilometer Nile, the world's second longest river and
Africa's longest, runs 1,530 kilometers across Egypt south-north
before pouring into the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
With a deficient rainfall over the entire country, human
existence in Egypt depends closely on irrigation from the Nile,
resulting in acute concentration of nearly 98 percent of the
population in the Nile Valley, only 4 percent of the country's
total area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Share Anti-AIDS Experience with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 7 (Xinhua) --The Uganda AIDS Commission is ready to
share its experience with Zimbabwean experts in combating AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The Commission's board-member Yona Kanyomozi made the remarks
Tuesday when meeting with a 17-member Zimbabwean delegation which
is on a week-long visit to Uganda, Uganda News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kanyomozi briefed the guests on the history of AIDS/HIV in
Uganda, Ugandans' perception of the disease, and government's
efforts for curbing the spread of the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has accepted to be one of the trial centers for the
AIDS vaccine as well as a cocktail of anti-AIDS drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is one of the countries in Africa which is succeeding
in combating the deadly disease. The HIV infection in Uganda has
dropped from 13 to 9.5 percent between 1994 and 1997 as a result
of increased HIV/AIDS awareness.
</P>
<P>
Oppah Rushesha, the head of the Zimbabwean delegation which is
made up of ministers, members of parliament, youths and
journalists, said Zimbabwe still lacks the necessary skills
and the political will to help its own anti-AIDS program achieve
the success that Uganda has already registered.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Deputy Minister for Health and Child Welfare David
Parirenyatwa said 1.5 million Zimbabweans are HIV positive while
350,000 people in the country have developed fully-blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
