<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Nanobacteria May Cause Kidney Stones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Finnish researchers said that
the tiny little bacteria -- nanobacteria -- could be the cause of
kidney stones by building a mineral shell, according to Tuesday's
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences,
Finnish researchers Olavi Kajander and Neva Ciftcioglu of the
University of Kuopio said they found the bacteria in human blood
serum and also in kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
"Nanobacteria are the smallest cell-walled bacteria, only
recently discovered in human and cow blood and commercial cell
culture serum," they wrote.
</P>
<P>
They tested human and cow serum, and found nanobacteria in
both. When they let the serum sit in a test tube for a little
while, the bacteria settled on the bottom. They quickly developed
a thick mineral shell of apatite. These apatite shelters were
apparently the dwelling place of the organisms, they wrote.
</P>
<P>
They thus concluded these could be the starting points of
kidney stones, which build up layer by layer, just like a pearl
forming on a piece of sand inside an oyster.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish researchers found nanobacteria in all 30 people
with kidney stones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
