<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-07 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Bilateral Agreement on Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran said Tuesday that it would not
recognize any bilateral agreement to divide the Caspian Sea into
national sectors for exploiting its resources, Tehran radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi was quoted as
saying that a legal regime on the Caspian should be determined by
all of the five littoral states, and Iran would not accept any
bilateral agreement that is not in the interests of all.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi's words came in response to an agreement signed
Monday by Russia and Kazakhstan to divide the northern part of
Caspian Sea into separate Russian and Kazak sectors.
</P>
<P>
The five nations bordering the world's largest inland water
have been at adds for years over who owns the oil and natural gas
in the seabed.
</P>
<P>
The three nations with oil near their coastlines - Kazakhstan,
Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan - want the water divided into national
sectors so they can claim the oil for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Russia, two nations with little or no oil near their
Caspian coasts, want equal exploitation of the sea's riches.
</P>
<P>
Russia softened its position to sign the agreement with
Kazakhstan Monday. The deal could open the door for additional
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi urged all the five states to respect the 1996 joint
communique on the Caspian, which calls for joint efforts to
complete the legal regime.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Iran's call Monday for a speedup in completing
the legal regime for a fair and equal exploitation of the Caspian
resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
