<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Rejects UN's Upgrading Palestinian Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Tuesday rejected the
United Nations General Assembly's decision to upgrade the
Palestinian status, saying it contradicts the principles of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This decision creates a negative precedent and contradicts
the principles of the peace process and the spirit of the Oslo
Accords," said a statement issued by the Israeli Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The statement accused the Palestine Liberation Organization
(PLO) of "exploiting the United Nations on matters" that should be
settled by the bilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The General Assembly's decision, and its appendix, does not
change the status of the PLO as an organization with observer
status only at the U.N.," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
It demanded the PLO not take unilateral actions in the
international arena which would harm the peace process, while
urging the international community not to accept such actions.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly approved an Arab-sponsored resolution early
Tuesday to upgrade the PLO status from an observer to that of a
near statehood. The voting was 124 votes in favor, four against
with 10 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, frustrated by the prolonged impasse in the
peace process, launched the campaign last month to upgrade its
status in the UN. Israel has since been seeking help from
the United States and the European Union in an effort to
prevent the UN from approving such a resolution.
</P>
<P>
As expected, the U.S. voted against the resolution, arguing
that this would not help revive the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
