<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Authorities Concerned about Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African Labor
Department Tuesday expressed concern about safety standards in
construction industry following the death of 13 workers in the
Bushbuckridge Bridge disaster on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The department said it would investigate if health and safety
standards were violated before the bridge under construction
collapsed, killing 13 people and injuring 16.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was being built over the Marite River at Injaka
Dam, about 10 km from Bushbuckridge in Mpumalanga Province in
northeast South Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the Labor Department, in 1997 there were 530
accidents in the construction industry which resulted in 71
deaths.
</P>
<P>
"It is apparent that drastic measures are needed to address
this appalling state of affairs," the department said, noting an
investigation will be launched soon to determine the cause of the
Bushbuckridge Bridge disaster.
</P>
<P>
Concor, the company responsible for building the bridge, has
also launched an investigation, as have police forensic experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
