<HEADLINE> Chubais: Decision on IMF Loan to Russia Likely This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia's top negotiator with
international monetary organizations said Tuesday that decision on
a stabilization loan to Russia would be made before the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, President Boris Yeltsin's special liaison to
international financial organizations, made the remarks after
meeting Tuesday with officials of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Chubais had said earlier that Moscow needs 10 to 15 billion
U.S. dollars in loans to stabilize the economy and prop up the
ruble, the national currency that is under increasing pressure for
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
His remarks helped to ease the plunge in Russian stock markets,
where blue chips tumbled 8-10 percent in the first two hours of
Tuesday against Monday's close. Most of the shares ended the day
down 3-5 percent from their Monday levels.
</P>
<P>
Chubais said he and Martin Gilman, head of the IMF office in
Moscow, Michael Carter, head of the World Bank's office in Moscow,
and Jose Marques-Ruarte, deputy director of the IMF's European II
Department, would meet again at noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We will meet in order to settle the remaining issues and fix
possible differences," Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the credit is very important for Russia, but
it is also clear that we need to make our own efforts, without
which the crisis cannot be overcome."
</P>
<P>
Gilman of the IMF said Tuesday's meeting produced a list of key
problems which Russia, the IMF and the World Bank need to agree on
within the next week.
</P>
<P>
Carter, for his part, urged Moscow to go through serious
structural reform to move the economy forward, saying the World
Bank would do its best to back such efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
