<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abiola Dead  (more details) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's prominent political
detainee Moshood Abiola died of cardiac arrest at 4:00 p.m.
(local time ) Tuesday, at the age of 60, according to a government
statement issued in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Abiola was having a meeting with visiting United States
Under-Secretary of State Thomas Pickering, when he started
coughing and was hurried to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Abuja told Xinhua that he died on
the way to hospital .
</P>
<P>
The politician-businessman was widely believed to be winner of
the June 12, 1993 presidential elections. His release has been
seen as of crucial importance to the military government's
transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
Last week, visiting United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and his Commonwealth counterpart Emeka Anyaoku said the
military government had agreed to free Abiola very soon, along with
all the other political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who held a private talk with Abiola, said the man
looked hearty and healthy.
</P>
<P>
Some pictures Anyaoku exhibited to newsmen at a press
conference here a week ago showed a smiling Abiola who seemed to
be in good health.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government was expected to announce Abiola's
release any time from Wednesday at the end of the one-month
national mourning for late head of state, General Sani Abacha who
died suddenly of heart attack on June 8.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has reportedly ordered a postmortem
examination to determine the possible causes of Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
The Cable News Network quoted senior U.S. delegation officials
as saying that the death looks like a natural one.
</P>
<P>
But one of Abiola's daughters, Wura Abiola, claimed that she
believed her father was murdered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
