<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling South African Currency Affects Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
currency Rand's sharp drop against the U.S. Dollar is not only
affecting South African market, but also having a negative impact
on neighboring Swaziland, sources reaching here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hanson Dlamini, Swaziland economic affairs assistant
statistician, said Swaziland's currency, the Emalangeni, was
pinned to the Rand and therefore directly affected by the Rand's
performance on world markets.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Rand has slipped from less than five to
about 6.4 against the Dollar and 10.63 against the British Pound.
</P>
<P>
This poor performance had caused nervousness among many Swazi
businessmen and major industries who feared higher inflation and
job losses, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We currently export around 80 percent of our goods to South
Africa and we are already nervous about the South African
government's recent decision to charge 14 percent VAT (value
added tax) on goods coming into the country from neighboring
states," Dlamini said.
</P>
<P>
"Only imports which are entirely produced in South Africa will
not have any impact on us because the value of the Rand is
equivalent to the Emalangeni."
</P>
<P>
He said Swaziland exported almost 90 percent of its sugar to
countries other than South Africa and would be forced to increase
the price of its exports to counter the effect of hikes in import
prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
