<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Hand over Rwandan Genocide Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa confirmed Tuesday that the government has a list of
suspects of the 1994 Rwanda genocide who are said to be in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks while responding to a question
at a press conference held at the end of Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimungu's three-day visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He said the allegations are being examined and will be
forwarded to the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda
(ICTR), based in Arusha in north Tanzania, for appropriate
action.
</P>
<P>
The court was established by the United Nations to try chief
suspects of Rwanda's 1994 genocide. Over 500,000 Tutsis and
moderate Hutus were killed by Hutu extremists in a three-month
slaughter that ended with the Tutsi-dominated Rwanda Patriotic
Front seizing power.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that his government will try its best to
speed up the process of scrutinizing allegations and that the
suspects will be handed over to the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
"The best I can say is that we are working on the allegations
and relevant steps will be taken against the culprits because we
don't like killers or like to see the slayers walking around our
streets."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu urged people
who fled the country to go back, assuring them that the domestic
situation has improved.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu also welcomed foreign businessmen to invest in his
country, saying the government has taken various measures to
create a conducive investment atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate has lowered to one digit, standing at
around eight percent, he said, adding "We have stabilized the
foreign currency. We have reduced administrative procedures..."
</P>
<P>
He said the country is generally peaceful in spite of isolated
incidents of attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan President stressed that what is happening in his
country cannot be generalized as a situation that security is
deteriorating throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
