<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Refutes Charges of Violating CFE Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia Tuesday rejected U.S. charges
that Moscow has departed from its commitments under the
Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) treaty, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin made the
remarks in response to a U.S. government report to Congress that
accuses Russia of "handing over Armenia armaments which are
subject to the treaty."
</P>
<P>
"The CFE does not limit or control exports of conventional
armaments," Rakhmanin said. "It merely sets limits of
availability."
</P>
<P>
"The matter is an issue to be considered by the trilateral
Russian-Azerbaijani-Armenian commission," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the report's claim that Russia had stationed
its armed forces in Moldova without the latter's consent.
</P>
<P>
"It is a well-known fact that an agreement on the legal status
of Russian Federation armed forces which are temporarily on
Moldovan territory and on a procedure and schedule for their
withdrawal, although it has not been ratified by the two sides,
has been working normally since 1994," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed "extreme dissatisfaction" with the way the
CFE treaty was being adapted, saying Russia "still has not
received the details of NATO's commitment to refrain from
`additional stationing of substantial combat forces' outside from
the territory of the 16 (NATO member countries)."
</P>
<P>
"There has been no progress on the issue of restrictive
measures for air forces," the spokesman said, noting that it
remained unclear "how, after its expansion, NATO will account for
CFE levels for some categories of conventional armaments."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
