<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Warns Insurers Against Illegally Denying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday demanded that health insurance companies abide by a 1996
law that bars them from denying coverage based on pre-existing
conditions when workers change jobs.
</P>
<P>
Making an announcement at the White House, Clinton sent the
message to health insurers: "If you say `no' to people with
pre-existing conditions, the federal government will say `no' to
you."
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed an executive order directing the Office of
Personnel Management to inform insurers covering federal employees
that they must meet all the requirements of the 1996
Kennedy-Kassebaum health insurance law or lose their federal
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wants to make clear to insurance companies that they
must certify they are complying with the law if they intend to do
business with the federal government. Clinton's order affects 350
health plans offered to federal employees and their families.
</P>
<P>
The president said he was acting out of concern over reports
that some insurance companies were denying health benefits to
people with pre-existing conditions when they changed jobs.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, co-sponsored by Senator Edward M. Kennedy, a
Democrat, and former Senator Nancy Kassebaum Baker, a Republican,
people moving from one job to another are supposed to be promptly
eligible for coverage through the new employer if it provides
health benefits to employees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
