<HEADLINE> Arafat Welcomes UN's Decision on Palestinian Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
welcomed here Tuesday the United Nations General Assembly's
decision to upgrade the Palestinian U.N. status.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Xinhua, Arafat said the U.N. move represented "the
international support for peace."
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials added that the latest development
was "a huge step towards the imminent declaration of an
independent Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the statement after the U.N. General Assembly voted
to approve an Arab-sponsored resolution to upgrade the status of
the Palestine Liberation Organization from an observer to that of
a near statehood. The voting was 124 votes in favor, four against,
with 10 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel denounced the U.N. move as a violation of the
Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Jerusalem, Israeli Foreign Ministry
flatly rejected the U.N. decision, saying it contradicts the
principles of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This decision creates a negative precedent and contradicts
the principles of the peace process and the spirit of the Oslo
Accords," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, frustrated by the deep impasse in the peace
process, launched the campaign last month to upgrade its
U.N. status in a bid to protest against Israeli policy of
intransigence that has stalled the peace process for 16 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
