<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Continues Mediation Between Ethiopia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Tuesday ended his two-day visit to Eritrea and left for Ethiopia
to continue his search for peaceful resolution to the armed
conflict between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
In his brief remarks before leaving Eritrea for Ethiopia
Tuesday morning, Museveni said Uganda supports regional and
international efforts as well as Rwandan government's initiative
to solve the border dispute, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Eritrean and Ethiopian leaders are additional
to the efforts by the Organization of African Unity, the United
States and Rwanda in this direction, he added.
</P>
<P>
Museveni acknowledged that this visit provides a good
opportunity for him to learn about the causes leading to the
strained relations between Eritrea and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
When asked by the Ethiopian News Agency how he plans to end
the conflict, Museveni said he had not come with any
pre-conceived ideas but hoped these would emerge during his talks
with the leaders of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Museveni was accompanied by First Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the hostility between the two neighboring countries
flared into armed conflict along their border area, claiming
lives and causing heavy damages to properties.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea, a former Italian and British colony, won independence
from Ethiopia in 1993, making Ethiopia which used to enjoy a
1,000-kilometer-long sea shore into a land-locked country.
</P>
</TEXT>
