<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Warns Against Kosovo's Union with Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos warned on Tuesday that threats of military
intervention in the Serbian province of Kosovo by the west are
encouraging secession with Albania.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos, who is on a visit to the United States, told a
press conference here that Greece would oppose the union or
secession of Kosovo with Albanian, saying it would be
"intolerable."
</P>
<P>
"This cannot be tolerated because it leads to a change in
borders, which is extremely dangerous as an idea for the whole of
the area," Tsohatzopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the threats by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) only encourage the Kosovo Liberation Army to
fight on in the hope that the alliance would intervene against
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The role of NATO, he said, must be to encourage negotiations
between Milosevic and Rugova and to discourage any solutions by
military means and the use of violence.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
should hold serious peace talks with Ibrahim Rugova, who has been
recognized by ethnic Albanians as their political leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
