<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Political Uncertainty Looms over Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chang Yong)
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The sudden death of Moshood Abiola,
Nigeria's prominent political detainee, has increased the
uncertainty which has already been looming over the most populous
nation in Africa since the death of former head of state Sani
Abacha a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, who has been expected to play a key role in settling
the current political crisis in the country, died Tuesday
afternoon at the age of 60, according to a government statement.
</P>
<P>
Abiola was having a meeting with a United States delegation
headed by Under-Secretary of State Thomas Pickering in the
capital Abuja, when he started coughing and was hurried to
hospital.
</P>
<P>
He died of cardiac arrest at about 4:00 p.m. local time, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
But sources from Abuja told Xinhua that Abiola died on the way
to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Abiola was the second important figure of the country passing
away within one month.
</P>
<P>
The country's former head of state, late General Sani Abacha,
also died of heart attack on June 8, and a month-long nationwide
mourning has just concluded.
</P>
<P>
U.S. delegation officials were quoted as saying that Abiola's
death looked like a natural one. But one of his daughters, Wura
Abiola, claimed her father was murdered.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has reportedly ordered a postmortem
examination to determine the possible causes of Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
The detained politician-businessman died at a time when people
in and outside the west African country had been waiting for his
release so that he could be playing expected key role in the
military government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
Abiola's forthcoming release was announced by the new military
government after wide consultations with various interest groups,
including the opposition, and the international community
represented by United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
his Commonwealth counterpart Emeka Anyaoku.
</P>
<P>
Born on August 24, 1937 in Abeokuta, Ogun State in
southwestern Nigeria, the business mogul married four wives with
many children.
</P>
<P>
As the former presidential candidate of the disbanded Social
Democratic Party, Abiola was widely believed to have won the
presidential elections on June 12, 1993, the first of its kind in
a decade in the west African nation.
</P>
<P>
However, the then military government under General Ibrahim
Babangida announced that the polls had been marred by widespread
irregularities, and annulled the election.
</P>
<P>
After declaring himself head of state and president of a
parallel government, Abiola was arrested by security forces on
June 23, 1994 when he emerged from hiding to attend a rally in
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
Campaigns for his release have since been launched both in and
outside Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Like the sudden death of Abacha, the death of Abiola would
also have a great impact on the country's political transition
process.
</P>
<P>
According to Abacha's transition to civil rule program, this
year is the last year of military rule in Nigeria. The handover
date has been fixed for October 1.
</P>
<P>
When Abacha died a month ago, he left the country with no
presidential candidate because he had just been adopted by all
the five political parties as their sole and consensus
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
With the new government led by General Abdulsalam Abubakar
assumed office on June 9, there have been increasing appeals from
both at home and abroad that Abiola be freed to participate in
the political transition program.
</P>
<P>
The opposition in the country even demands that Abiola lead a
government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
It was announced last week that Abiola had told Annan that he
would not insist on his presidential candidacy after his release.
</P>
<P>
But this does not mean he would not involve in political
activities. And people are still expecting that he would take
part in the remaining part of the transition program by engaging
himself in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Amidst speculations that some secret deals have been done
between Abiola and the military government to solve the country's
political crisis, his sudden death, which came as a shock to many
Nigerians and foreigners, may add uncertainty to the transition
program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
