<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Offers Provisional Blessing to WorldCom, MCI Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Wednesday
gave a conditional green light to the proposed merger of two
U.S. telecommunications giants, WorldCom and MCI Communications
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, executive arm of the 15-member EU,
demanded total divestiture of MCI's assets in the market of
Internet-related services in return for the clearance.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the commission, which has responsibility for
ensuring fair competition within the single market, came after it
found significant overlaps by the two companies in the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
The two communication giants responded positively with a
proposed package of divestments including all of MCI's Internet
assets to eliminate the overlap in the Internet business.
</P>
<P>
The two companies had previously offered a limited assets sale, but
the commission judged it as insufficient.
</P>
<P>
WorldCom, the fourth largest U.S. long-distance telephone
company had made an unsolicited bid for MCI, the second largest
U.S. long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
If the merger succeeds, it will create a telecoms giant
second only to AT&AMP;T in size. 
</P>
</TEXT>
