<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Trade Unions Plan Nationwide Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia's independent trade unions
are planning a nationwide strike for early October to protest against
government economic policy and to demand President Boris Yeltsin's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Wednesday at a conference of the
Federation of Independent Trade Unions (FITU), the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move came amid rising protests around the country where
miners who failed to get their wages for months blocked railways
in Siberia and the far north, costing the economy tens of
millions Roubles.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways said the week-long blockade of the
Trans-Siberian Railroad had cost the country 12.3 million roubles
(about 2.05 million U.S. dollars) in losses.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four cargo trains are now standing idle on the
Trans-Siberian Railroad and many more have been sent along detour
routes. Passenger trains, however, are allowed to pass freely.
</P>
<P>
At the Wednesday FITU meeting, participants agreed that the
country was undergoing a profound social and economic crisis and
that trade unions should do their best to prevent a further
decline in living standards.
</P>
<P>
Defense industry workers have also joined the wave of
protests over wage arrears.
</P>
<P>
In an open letter to Yeltsin's representative in Udmurtia on
Wednesday, union leaders from defense enterprises said the federal
government would have to pay back wages before September or
face "greater activity in demanding the resignation of the
government and the president", Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The open letter said a subsistence income in the region was 409
rubles (about 48 dollars) a month, but the workers got only 100 to
200 rubles (16.6 to 33.3 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
