<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Ukrainian counterpart Leonid Kuchma agreed Wednesday to meeti
in Kharkov, Ukraine in September.
</P>
<P>
Discussing the prospects of bilateral cooperations on the
phone, the two leaders agreed that the summit, scheduled for
September 18-19, should also involve top government ministers, the
Interfax News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma's press service said they also discussed ways to step up
economic interaction and implementation of joint projects.
</P>
<P>
It added the Yeltsin-Kuchma conversation took place "in a warm and
friendly atmosphere".
</P>
<P>
The summit is seen as another sign of improving relations between
Moscow and Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma paid his first official visit to Moscow last February
when he and Yeltsin signed a 10-year economic cooperation treaty.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed three agreements on the division of
the Black Sea fleet and a treaty on bilateral friendship and
cooperation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, sticking points still remained. Russia's State Duma,
the lower house of parliament, decided in May to delay discussing
the ratification of the Russian-Ukrainian friendship treaty
because of Kiev's refusal to rule out the possibility of joining
NATO.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is adamantly opposed to NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
