Chitauro made the remarks when she was opening the 1998 institute
of personnel management of Zimbabwe annual convention in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The minister said it was indisputable that people were the
ingredient for success in any business organization, whether
private or public.
</P>
<P>
''The development of human resources and the subsequent
empowerment will culminate in the establishment of a sound
macro-economic environment and reduce poverty effectively,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
The success of the Zimbabwe program for economic and social
transformation hinged on increased productivity in the country's
industries, hence the need for upgrading workers' skills, she
said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, a national productivity center should be
established through which government, the private sector and
labor could contribute toward improving productivity, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
She added, ''the involvement of all stake-holders is,
therefore, of paramount importance as envisaged benefits will
cascade to all strata of society.''
</P>
<P>
The two-day convention with the theme of ''the Power of
People'' would, among other issues, discuss the role of human
resources in the current skewed economic environment. 
