<HEADLINE> Moscow Denounces Seoul's Diplomat Expulsion as Unwarranted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister
Grigory Karasin has condemned South Korea's expulsion of a Russian
diplomat as "absolutely unwarranted".
</P>
<P>
Seoul's action was "an absolutely unwarranted and inequitable
response to what has happened in Russia", Karasin said Wednesday
referring to Moscow's expulsion last week of a South Korean
diplomat accused of espionage.
</P>
<P>
Cho Sung-woo, a councillor of the South Korean embassy, was
caught meeting a top Russian Foreign Ministry official. He was
declared persona non grata Saturday and ordered to leave the
country in 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's expulsion of Oleg Abramkin, first secretary of
the Russian embassy in Seoul, was an apparent retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Karasin, who had informed South Korean Ambassador Lee In-ho
earlier Wednesday of Russia's stance, said it was Seoul that he
held responsible.
</P>
<P>
The move by South Korea was "an unprovoked escalation of
tension in Russian-Korean relations", he said, adding: "The
responsibility for the possible consequences of this decision will
be borne by the Korean side."
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat who was caught meeting Cho was identified
as Valentin Moiseyev, deputy director of the Russian Foreign
Ministry's First Asian Department.
</P>
<P>
Moiseyev was formally taken into custody Monday pending trial
on espionage charges. If convicted of high treason as prescribed
in the Russian Criminal Code, he could face up to 20 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
Russia and South Korea established diplomatic ties in 1990 and
have since enjoyed good relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
