<HEADLINE> AL Praises U.N. for Upgrading Palestinian Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary-General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid Wednesday spoke highly of the resolution passed
by the U.N. General Assembly to upgrade the Palestine's status in
the international body.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, Abdel-Meguid described the resolution as
an important step toward the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly adopted the Arab-sponsored resolution
Tuesday to upgrade Palestine's status from observer to nonvoting
member, which is near statehood.
</P>
<P>
The voting was 124 for, four against, with 10 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Israel, the United States and two Pacific island countries -
the Marshall Islands and Micronesia - voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
With new powers at hand, Palestinian representatives can raise
issues of the peace process in the assembly and co-sponsor draft
resolutions on Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
But the representatives can not vote or put forward candidates
for U.N. committees, such as the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation Arab organization has expressed hopes Tuesday
that the resolution would be followed by similar steps to bring a
just and comprehensive peace to the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
