<HEADLINE> Philippines Creates Anti-organized Crime Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada is expected
to issue within the next two days an order creating a presidential
commission against organized crime which shall oversee the
operations of a special task force that will go after organized
syndicates.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed Wednesday by Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora after a meeting with Estrada on the composition of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the commission shall include members from some
non-governmental anti-crime institutions to ensure the cooperation
between government law enforcers and the private sector in the
arrest and prosecution of criminals.
</P>
<P>
He said the secretary of interior and local governments is
expected to be named as the head of the commission, whose exact
title has yet to be worked out when the order is finally drafted.
</P>
<P>
As originally envisioned, a task force shall be created to
direct the operations of elements of the National Bureau of
Investigation (NBI), the Philippine National Police (PNP) and
other law enforcement agencies, in going after organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the commission will be reporting directly to the
president, to keep him abreast of the progress of the fight
against crime.
</P>
<P>
The quashing of major organized crime syndicates is among the
priorities of the new administration during its first six months
in office.
</P>
<P>
Among the organized crimes that will be handled by the
commission are kidnapping, bank robberies, drug trafficking and
manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
