<HEADLINE> China Getting Tougher on Maritime Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Public Security officer
said today that China is prepared to crack down on illegal
maritime activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that on April 26, Chinese border troops seized an oil
tanker, the M.T.Wilby, on the sea near Wenchang on the island
province of Hainan, which was flying the flag of the Republic of
Honduras and was involved in smuggling activities.
</P>
<P>
After an investigation, the police discovered that the oil
tanker's real name was the "PETRO RANGER" and that it belonged to
Malaysia and had been hired by a Singaporean company. It had
33 crew members, and 12 were accused by the other 21 of being
hijackers.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior official, the oil tanker and the 21
crew members were released on May 28, and the 12 accused crew
members are still being detained for further investigation.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that Chinese police made a special
effort to see to it that the oil tanker would be properly
maintained and that the crew members would be looked after, that
they could have health examinations and receive any medical
treatment they might need, and any other things they might
need. 
</P>
</TEXT>
