<HEADLINE> Philippines, U.S. to Hold Defense Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines-U.S. Mutual Defense
Board will hold its first regular meeting Friday in Quezon City in
Metro Manila, a military spokesman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Col. Gregorio Fajardo, public information officer of the
Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP), said the meeting will be
jointly presided by AFP chief Lt. Gen. Joselin Nazareno and
Admiral Joseph Prueher, U.S. Commander-in-Chief for the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Fajardo said the defense board would discuss the regional
security situation, bilateral cooperative activities and the
results of a joint security seminar between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The board was created in May 1958 as provided for by the
Philippines-U.S. Mutual Defense Treaty signed in August 1951.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the board has been conducting meetings on a regular
basis in Honolulu and Manila respectively.
</P>
<P>
The board is aimed at encouraging direct liaison and
consultation between the two countries on military matters of
mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Fajardo said the board would serve as a forum for the
coordination of bilateral activities such as joint training
exercises, humanitarian assistance, relief operations during
natural disasters, ship visits and sea and air transit. 
</P>
