<HEADLINE> Egypt Says Strategic Dialog With U.S. Wide-Ranging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said Wednesday that the Egyptian-American strategic dialog in
Washington starting Friday would not be limited to discussions of
U.S. economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Expressing hope for the success of the talks, Moussa told an
Egyptian Television program that it would tackle not only the
current bilateral economic relationship, but also various spheres
of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"It is not right for the dialog to be limited to the next five
or 10 years of U.S. assistance to Egypt," he told "Good Morning
Egypt" program Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian economy is progressing and is moving away from
dependence on foreign aid toward self reliance, he added.
</P>
<P>
But like several other Egyptian ministers who have visited
Washington in the past few weeks, Moussa is most likely to discuss
how to use the U.S. economic aid to serve Egypt's switch to market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is considering cutting this aid according to its
policy of reducing foreign economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, as the first Arab country to seal peace with Israel,
gets a total of 815 million U.S. dollars in U.S. economic aid and
1.3 billion dollars in military aid every year.
</P>
<P>
The economic relationship with the U.S. is a key relationship,
Moussa said. "The U.S. is a big market and a strong ally in the
global economy, and it is beneficial to have an active and
positive U.S.-Egyptian relationship."
</P>
<P>
Moussa is to arrive in Washington Thursday and talk with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on creating a fast
communication channel between the U.S. State Department and the
Egyptian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said the dialog with the U.S. involves two aspects,
bilateral and regional.
</P>
<P>
At the bilateral level, Egypt is to open door for trade with
the U.S., and to increase investments in many fields. There are
other issues such as transfer of technology, and scientific,
educational and cultural relations, which will be discussed,
Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
On regional issues, Moussa said the realization of Middle East
peace, which is Egypt's main interest, will be tackled. If the
process that was agreed upon in the 1991 Madrid Peace Conference
was steered off course, he said, "it is our task now to put it
back on track."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is becoming totally aware of the different aspects of
the current situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We all want peace, and we will turn the page when Palestinian
land is restored, their political rights are regained and Israel
and Arab countries receive their security," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa met here Tuesday with Albright's envoy, Greg Craig, who
came to add final touches on the preparation for the upcoming
Egypt-U.S. strategic dialog in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
