<HEADLINE> Population Growth, Challenge to Africa: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Rapid population growth presents a
challenge to African countries which must provide health care,
housing, schools, employment and food for an increasing number of
people, a Zimbabwean minister said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a media workshop on population and
development here, Zimbabwean Minister of Information, Posts and
Telecommunications Chen Chimutengwende challenged communication
agencies to highlight implications of population dynamics.
</P>
<P>
"The shortcomings have now caught up with us and manifest
themselves with the characteristic pressure on almost all
resources," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He told journalists and other attendants that the world's
population growth is alarming and that the situation remains out
of control despite the implementation of sound population
policies by governments.
</P>
<P>
The minister said 97 percent of the increase in population for
the next 60 years would be in developing countries, while 34
percent is expected to be contributed by Africa alone.
</P>
<P>
The one-day workshop was funded by United Nations Population
Fund. 
</P>
