<HEADLINE> Centralized Foreign Investment Board Proposed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Merchant
Banks in Malaysia (AMBM) has proposed the setting up of a
Centralized Foreign Investment Board along with other remedies and
strategies to actively bring back foreign investments into the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum submitted to the Ministry of Finance's ongoing
1999 Budget Dialogue Wednesday, AMBM said the setting up of the
one-stop centralized foreign investment board would serve not only
as a marketing and promotions authority but also act as a
centralized coordinator catering to foreigners wishing to invest
in any sector, thus playing a crucial role in the revival of the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed that the Foreign Investment Committee now be
reconstituted to carry out this role.
</P>
<P>
AMBM said that there was a capital outflow of about 20 billion
ringgit (5 billion U.S. dollars) from the country from mid-1997 to
end-1997 and added that reversing the capital outflow would lead
to a reversal in the depreciating trend of the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
It would also restore much needed funding to the economy and
therefore give rise to a sustainable reduction in interest rates,
it said.
</P>
<P>
AMBM said that the capital inflow would restore confidence,
stimulate the economy and strengthen the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Towards this end, AMBM said there is a need to address various
misperceptions about Malaysia's attitude to foreign investors and
ease the flow of accurate information on foreign investments
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Other measures proposed to attract foreign investments are the
promulgation of clear guidelines on foreign equity participation
and ownership, especially those related to property, clarifying
the issue of divestment of foreign owned assets to local entities
and removing bureaucratic bottlenecks, AMBM said.
</P>
<P>
It said the government should also consider reviewing the
existing framework for foreign venture capital companies to be
based in Malaysia and strengthening tax incentives relating to the
inflow of foreign capital and repatriation and reinvestment of
profits and the length of time foreign capital remains in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The key macroeconomic strategies should be targeted at reducing
the real and perceived risk premium on Malaysia, AMBM said, adding
that the pivotal requirement of this is the undertaking of a
systematic and meticulously outlined resolution of the large
domestic stock of outstanding debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
