<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Sets Minimum Reserves Requirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
has decided to require minimum reserves from commercial banks to
help steer interest rates and money supply for the 11 founding
countries of the single European currency, the euro, which is to
be launched next year.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the monthly meeting of ECB's governing
council in Frankfurt Tuesday, ECB president Wim Duisenberg said in
Frankfurt Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, commercial banks are obliged to set aside a
certain percentage of their deposits at the central bank each
month, paving the way for the central bank to monitor bank lending
and fine tune money supply in the market.
</P>
<P>
The exact ratio of the required minimum reserves will be set
this autumn and could fall between 1.5 percent and 2.5 percent,
said Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
But the plan has met with reservations from some experts
fearing it would lead to less competitiveness among European
commercial banks against their U.S. counterparts which carry no
minimum reserves demand.
</P>
<P>
Defending the plan, Duisenberg said the ECB would pay interest
to commercial banks on their reserves lodged at the central bank
to offset the possible disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
The decision is viewed as a victory for the powerful German
central bank, the Bundesbank, which has persistently lobbied for
the system to ensure the stability of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland will launch the
euro in January next year.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Denmark have opted out of the first wave for the
euro, while Greece and Sweden were judged by the E.U. not
economically ready to join. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karachi Stock Exchange Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi Stock Exchange (KSE)
-100 Index plunged by 19 points or 2.1 percent Wednesday to close
at 866.71 points.
</P>
<P>
The KSE-100 Index dropped following rumors that Pakistan's
ongoing talks with officials from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) in Islamabad have made no headway, said dealers.
</P>
<P>
"Share market was moving steadily during the first session but
premature rumors of negative nature pushed the selling pressure in
the stock market during second session," said a leading stock
broker.
</P>
<P>
He said that investors here were eagerly looking forward to the
announcement by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz in Islamabad on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Aziz was supposed to address a press conference at 4 p.m. but
it was deferred to 6 p.m. due to unexplained reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Our domestic investors are very skeptic and had resorted to
heavy selling across the board in blue chips," said another stock
dealer.
</P>
<P>
Total market capitalization in stocks plunged by 4.6 billion
(46 rupees to one U.S. dollar) to 258 billion rupees from 263.4
billion rupees a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
Total trading volume at KSE Wednesday was recorded at 99.07
million shares compared with 69.6 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Share prices of 42 scrips registered a plunge while 29 went up.
</P>
