<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirate (UAE) has decided to
postpone 35 percent of the projects that should have been
implemented from 1998 to 2002 for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
The UAE Planning Department said the projects need over 24
billion dirhams (6.5 billion U.S. dollars) while oil earnings
which constitute about 90 percent of the country's revenues
dropped dramatically due to sagging prices.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Trade volume between Jordan and Saudi Arabia has
jumped to 224 million dinars (about 316 million dollars) in 1997
from 80 million dinars (113 million dollars) in 1989, a report
released by the Amman Chamber of Industry Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's trade with Saudi Arabia represented 20 percent of its
total with Arab states in 1997, six percentage points up as
compared with 1989.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to Saudi Arabia accounted for 25 percent of
its total last year, as against 20 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian government has received three offers from the
Netherland, the U.S. and Australia for the construction and
management of the east Port Said harbor, which will cost 1.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian side will pay 40 percent of the cost, and foreign
companies bear the rest.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The final touches will soon be completed for the
signing of an agreement on the opening of the first navigation
line to link Egypt directly with Russian ports and harbors in the
Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic-language daily Alam Al Yom said Wednesday that the
project, which needs an investment of 40 million dollars, aims to
facilitate Egyptian exports.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia will host a two-day international conference
on July 14-16 to boost cooperation between African and Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
The conference will particularly discuss ways of promoting
cooperation among small and medium firms, as well as facilitating
capital flow between the continents, a source at the Tunisian
Ministry of International Cooperation and External Investment said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Negotiations between Iraq and a French firm to
establish a joint oil company have made great progress, an Iraqi
Oil Ministry source said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the source as saying that the
"Middle East Oil Drilling Company," specialized in oil drilling
and exploration, was Iraq's third oil joint venture to boost crude
production and export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
