<HEADLINE> Malaysia Puts More Money for Intelligent City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government has
approved an additional 600 million ringgit (150 million U.S.
dollars) for the development of its Cyberjaya, the world's first
intelligent city.
</P>
<P>
Cyberjaya, a multi-million ringgit project, is part of
Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), a 750 square kilometer
zone south of Kuala Lumpur designated as a hub for the development
of multimedia products and services.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Wednesday the
allocation reaffirmed the government's commitment to seeing the
MSC project through despite the current downturn in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The additional allocation is expected to be drawn from the
5-billion ringgit (1.25 billion U.S. dollars) Infrastructure Fund
announced by Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim last week, who had said that the fund would ensure that
provision of all basic infrastructure for the MSC would be on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The government is fully committed to the development of the
MSC and all the money we can afford will go into the project and
it will take off," Mahathir was quoted by Malaysia's national news
agency Bernama as saying after closing a conference on the MSC
here.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir described the MSC as a very important project for the
country and a logical step to take after attaining
industrialization, pledging "We are going ahead with the project."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir called on local small and medium scale information
technology companies to take advantage of the low cost in setting
up base within the MSC.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign participants are also welcomed. "We have always
laid out the welcome mat for them and we have been a good host,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said technologies and their applications were moving
so fast so much so that Malaysians needed to equip themselves to
face such development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
