<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-owned Enterprises Warned Against Brain Drain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Experts with the China Association
of Science and Technology today suggested that the state-owned
enterprises (SOE) should exercise controls on the number of
layoffs among their scientific staff members to avoid a brain
drain in their future development.
</P>
<P>
A survey, released by the association in Beijing today, showed
that in more than 400 SOEs surveyed across the country, people 50
and below accounted for more than two-thirds of the total number
of laid-off scientific workers.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that it will be beneficial to enterprises if they
give advanced training to young laid-off workers because they may
become the backbone of the future scientific work with improved
skills and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that the problem of laid-off
scientific staff members has plagued two-thirds of the SOEs
surveyed, and about 41 percent of those enterprises with good
economic returns still have the problem. The number of laid-off
scientific workers has already made up 5 percent of the total
scientific staff, or 5.7 percent of the total laid-off workers in
the 400 SOEs.
</P>
<P>
The re-employment of the laid-off scientific personnel seems
more difficult than that of the normal laid-off workers, since
most of the former do not want to find jobs in other cities or in
non-state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments at all levels should help laid-off
scientific workers change the traditional concept of working in
the same unit for their whole lives and encourage them to get new
starts in other units or in new careers, said Zhou Guangzhao,
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese National
People's Congress, and chairman of the China Association for
Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
He said the association will take it as a major task for this
year to help laid-off scientific workers find employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coronary Artery Disease High in South Asia: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Coronary artery disease that
reduces blood supply to the heart muscle and can lead to heart
attacks is more widespread in South Asia than other regions, said
a report in the recent issue of Current Science Journal.
</P>
<P>
Studies showed that South Asians in general are most prone to
coronary artery disease than other ethnic groups, said J. Dhawan
and S. Petkar from the Seunthorpe General Hospital in the United
Kingdom in the report published by the journal.
</P>
<P>
South Asians tend to develop the disease manifestations at an
earlier age and respond less well to treatment.
</P>
<P>
Studies in India suggest that prevalence of coronary artery
disease is 10 percent, four times higher than that of the United
States and similar to other South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Prevalence of the disease in rural India, where incidence is
much lower than in urban regions, is twice that of the United
states.
</P>
<P>
The two Indian scholars said in their report that South Asians
tend to suffer more from diabetes, higher insulin levels,
abdominal obesity, and lower levels of physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
While the exact cause of the higher mortality rate in South
Asians is yet to be determined, both genetic and environmental
factors play a role, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Official Confident of Overcoming Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Financial Secretary Donald Tsang
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region said here Wednesday
that the Airport Authority will be able to overcome the running-in
difficulties in the next few days and deliver back to the Hong
Kong people a world class airport.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions concerning the problems occurring at
the new Hong Kong International Airport since its commercial
operation on July 6, Tsang said that the Airport Authority had a
long period of running in and trial before the opening of the
airport, which was originally scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
"We must realize those trials were in very contrived
conditions, not tested with the number of passengers we handled
yesterday, and the amount of cargo. So it was a bit unlucky, and
the computer had a little bit of problem for them," the financial
secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Since its opening Monday, there has been chaos at the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok mainly in flights display board, cargo
operation and broken-down auxiliary facilities. The most serious
problem now is cargo delay.
</P>
<P>
Despite the problems, Tsang said that the Airport Authority has
been trying its very best. "They have been working day and night
and from the report I have received there have been very marked
improvements already over the last two days, particularly this
morning compared with yesterday," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure they'll be able to overcome this running-in
difficulties in the next few days. And we'll have to be fair too.
It is a first class airport. It's one of the largest airports in
the world... I'm sure they (the Airport Authority) are going to
deliver back to us the Hong Kong people a first class airport in
the next few days," Tsang noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
