<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Examines 20,000 Prosecutors, Anti-Corruption Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide campaign has been
launched to scrutinize the conduct of China's 20,000 leading
officials working at county- and city-level procuratorates and
anti-corruption bureaus.
</P>
<P>
"The major target will be focused on chief prosecutors and
heads of anti-corruption bureaus," according to a circular
distributed during a national tele-conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The circular was jointly issued in June by the Organization
Department of the Central Committee of the Communist Party (CPC)
of China and the Supreme People's Procuratorate. This
investigation is expected to be completed by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
This campaign was launched in response to directives given by
top Chinese leaders on preventing and curbing corruption inside
law-enforcement departments and to the "many pertinent opinions
and suggestions" put forward by delegates to the National People's
Congress earlier this year on procuratorial work, said Li Tielin,
deputy head of the CPC Central Committee Organization Department.
</P>
<P>
These officials will be checked for their political and
ideological quality, working style, self-discipline and honesty,
law-enforcement proficiency level, and procedures by which they
were elected and appointed, as well as the situations in the
departments under their charge, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
During the campaign, they will be asked to report on their own
work, and will be examined by their subordinates, deputies to
local people's congresses and party committees.
</P>
<P>
"The scale of the inspection campaign, which covers 3,700 local
procuratorates and anti-corruption bureaus, and the number of
people involved, up to 20,000, are unprecedented," said Li,
the Organization Department official.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu Kehui, deputy prosecutor-general of the Supreme
People's Procuratorate, city- and county-level procuratorates make
up 99 percent of the total number of prosecuting bodies in the
country, whose prosecutors account for 93 percent of the nation's
total, handling 95 percent of all criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
The leading officials of these bodies play a vital role in
safeguarding justice, she said.
</P>
<P>
Both Li and Hu told the tele-conference that the campaign,
under specialized leading groups in the localities, must avoid
perfunctory and superficial gestures, and expose real problems in
an effort to improve the working style and law-enforcement
proficiency of prosecuting bodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Sudan Agree to Establish Sea, Air Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Sudan have agreed
to establish sea and air links, Malaysian Transport Minister Ling
Liong Sik said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was agreed upon during talks between him and Sudanese
Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail here, he told reporters
later.
</P>
<P>
Ling said Malaysian and Sudanese officials and representatives
of both airlines would finalize the details within a month before
ratifying an air-link agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ling said for a start, their respective national flag carriers
-- Malaysia Airlines (MAS) and Sudan Air -- would exchange
passengers at Dubai.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that Sudan Air can sell MAS tickets
for traffic to Malaysia and beyond and likewise MAS can sell
tickets for Sudan-bound traffic and beyond, Ling said.
</P>
<P>
Ling said he explained to Mustafa the need for establishing air
links between the two countries because many Asians working in
Sudan would need an efficient air service to cater for their
traveling needs.
</P>
<P>
On sea links, Ling said both countries would encourage cargo
shipment from Port Klang, Malaysia, to Sudan especially through
the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa arrived here Monday on a five-day visit to Malaysia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
