<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Decision on Redeployment Taken at Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Both Israel's inner cabinet and
the wider security cabinet convened Wednesday morning, but no
decision was taken concerning the further redeployment in the West
Bank, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the inner cabinet, which groups Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, and Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky, was the first in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Both meetings took place following speculation in Israel that
a decision on the second withdrawal from the West Bank is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Netanyahu spoke on telephone with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Tuesday night to
discuss the redeployment. It quoted "senior sources" in Jerusalem
as saying that Israel and the U.S. have narrowed their gaps "on a
number of issues" although key differences remain.
</P>
<P>
The report has coincided with remarks made recently both by the
U.S. and Israeli officials that an Israeli decision on the second
redeployment, which they said would help bring a breakthrough in
the deadlocked peace process, will be taken soon.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Tuesday
that U.S. President Bill Clinton, Albright and Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross "have all been actively involved" in trying to
break the stalemate in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Monday night that she had had intensive
telephone contacts with Netanyahu in recent days and tried to
work it issue by issue. "I think we are coming closer," she said.
</P>
<P>
In Israel, Netanyahu contended Tuesday that the differences
which plagued his government's intermittent dealings with the
U.S. have been virtually resolved. Mordechai said a cabinet
decision on the redeployment could be made "within days."
</P>
<P>
The boldest prediction came from the Israeli newspaper the
Jerusalem Post, which on Wednesday quoted "a source" as saying
that at a forthcoming meeting, the inner cabinet would give a
conditional approval for the U.S. initiative calling for a 13
percent withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the ministers were likely to approve the
withdrawal package as long as the Palestinians agree to
Netanyahu's demands, including the arrest of terrorists and the
convening of the Palestinian National Council for the formal
revision of the Palestinian Covenant which calls for the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian National Authority issued a statement
Tuesday rejecting the terms set by the Israeli prime
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
