<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian President Calls on People to Work Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakiti Muluzi
has called on his people to work hard and adhere to their work
ethics at all times.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi said this Monday in Malawi's northern city of Mzuzu at
the climax of celebrations marking the 34th anniversary of the
country's independence, the Malawi News Agency (MANA) reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"At the time the present government is emphasizing on poverty
alleviation, it is incumbent upon everyone of us to play his part
in bringing about development which in the long run will
eradicate our socio-economic malady," said Muluzi.
</P>
<P>
"The path to social and economic development is not all that
rosy and cannot be achieved overnight but it is imperative for
all Malawians to work hard together as children of one family,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
"Laziness in the homes, work places and other sectors of the
economy cannot take us anywhere," Muluzi said. "Donors will only
help if ourselves are in the forefront in forging developmental
endeavors."
</P>
<P>
"Since 1994 when pluralist politics was ushered into this
country, my government has cultivated genuine relations with not
only our neighbors but with the rest of the continent and the
world at large," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malawi attained independence from Britain in 1964 and became a
republic in 1996. The country adopted a multi-party political
system in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
