<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Circular Issued Punishing Local Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Shengwen, former vice-mayor of
Harbin, capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, was
expelled from the Party for economic crimes.
</P>
<P>
Making public a circular issued by the Heilongjiang Provincial
Commission for Discipline Inspection, the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China (CPC) says
that Zhu served as secretary general and vice-mayor of the city
government of Harbin from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the circular says Zhu took 18 bribes worth
a total of more than 330,000 yuan (39,000 U.S. Dollars), and his
assets of 600,000 yuan came from unidentified sources, according
to authorities.
</P>
<P>
The circular states that Zhu's behavior severely betrayed the
power bestowed by the Party and the people, and damaged the image
of the Party and the government.
</P>
<P>
The circular also says that Party and government officials at
all levels should earnestly draw lessons from Zhu's case and
exercise their power for the Party and the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
