<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urges US, EU to Lift Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has urged the United States and the European
Union (EU) to lift their sanctions against Nigeria, which he said
has seriously affected the livelihood of ordinary Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the call Tuesday in Nigerian capital Abuja,
where he held talks with a high-level U.S. government delegation
headed by Thomas Pickering, the Under-secretary of State for
Political Affairs and former ambassador to the most populous
country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also includes General James Jamerson, Deputy
Commander of the U.S. European Command; Susan Rice, Assistant
Secretary of State for African Affairs and several other senior
U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar told the U.S. visitors that time is now ripe for the
various sanctions to be lifted as the livelihood of the Nigerians
is at stake.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has done a lot in the areas of drug control and
fighting against financial crimes to be considered for
certification, Abubakar said, adding that it is time for Nigeria
and the U.S. to reestablish air links and normalize their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian head of state assured that he would continue to
encourage the participation of all Nigerians in the social and
political transition process, irrespective of their political
persuasions.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said he would strengthen the ongoing consultations to
ensure that no viewpoint is ignored as no useful purpose would be
served by alienating groups just because of their views.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Pickering reportedly said the composition of
his group is a reflection of the importance the U.S. government
attached to the need to develop a close working relationship with
Nigeria, which he described as a great country.
</P>
<P>
Pickering said his government was pleased by the steps already
taken by Abubakar, referring to the release of some political
detainees and the pledge to continue the transition to democracy,
but he made it clear that there would be still a long way to go
in normalizing the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He commended the Nigerian military's role in peace-keeping
operations in various parts of the world, and urged Nigeria not
to miss the chance of playing a significant role not only in
Africa but also in the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the media at the end of the meeting from 10:30
a.m. to 12:35 a.m., Pickering said that "it was an extremely
productive and very informative meeting with the head of state."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other Western nations imposed sanctions on
Nigeria after the annulment of the June 12, 1993 presidential
election and stepped up their sanctions further in 1993 after the
hanging of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists by
the Nigerian government on charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include among others visa restrictions on senior
government officials, cut of air links, ban on sale of arms and
stoppage of training of Nigerian military officers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
