<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Reduce Air Pollution From LCPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission proposed
on Wednesday new limits for emissions of certain pollutants from
large combustion plants (LCPs).
</P>
<P>
The new limits for emissions of sulphur dioxide, nitrogen
oxides and dust are twice as strict as the existing ones and will
apply to all new installations put into operation after January 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposal enlarged the emission limitation to
include gas turbines and to set limits for nitrogen oxide
emissions.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is expected to encourage the use of combined heat
and power generation in new large combustion plants.
</P>
<P>
This form of generation is a technique that allows the use more
than 80 percent of the fuel's potential energy, compared with just
35 to 50 percent energy consumption in traditional techniques.
</P>
<P>
The extra costs resulting from the new limit values were
estimated to be at less than 2 billion European currency units
(ECU) over the first 10 years after their introduction.
</P>
<P>
The LCPs, with a capacity threshold of 50 megawatts, include
mostly large boilers used for the production of steam.
</P>
<P>
Around 500 power stations account for two thirds of the power
capacity of LCPs in the European Union while the other third is
divided among up to 2,000 installations on industrial sites in the
EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
