<HEADLINE> Statistics Show Continued Growth in China's Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade increased by
5.2 percent during the first half of this year with a total volume
amounting to 151.401 billion U.S. dollars, according to the latest
statistics from Customs.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that China's exports in the period
increased by 7.6 percent and its imports, by 2.2 percent over the
same period of last year, reaching 86.975 billion U.S. dollars and
64.425 billion U.S. dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign-trade surplus in this period reached 22.55
billion U.S. dollars, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of China's general trade during this period
reached 53.369 billion U.S. dollars, representing a 1.8 percent
increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
China's general trade export volume was 36.527 billion U.S.
dollars during the first six months, a 4.4 percent rise over the
same period last year, while its import volume was 16.842 billion
U.S. dollars, a decrease of 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's processing trade volume in the first half of this year
rose by 5.8 percent to 80.714 billion U.S. dollars, according to
the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Processing exports in the period reached 47.627 billion U.S.
dollars, and processing imports came to 33.087 billion
U.S. dollars, up 8.6 percent and 2.1 percent, respectively, over
the same period of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
