<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence in S. Africa Hits 5-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's business
confidence plunged to its worst level in five years last month
amid turmoil caused by the falling Rand, high interest rates and
a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
The Star newspaper Wednesday quoted the South African Chamber
of Commerce (Sacob) as saying that its business confidence index
dropped 5.7 points to 92.2 points in June against 97.9 points in
May. The index was unchanged at 99.1 in April.
</P>
<P>
"The recent speculation against the Rand and the concomitant
threat to financial stability emphasizes the vulnerability of
South Africa's financial markets in light of the country's
emerging market status and its balance of payments constraints,"
Sacob's Director-General Raymond Parsons said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Rand staged a surprise recovery to 6.10 Rand to one U.S.
Dollar Tuesday, after slumping to 6.75 Rand at its historic low
against the U.S. Dollar. It has lost over 30 percent of its
value against the U.S. Dollar since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
As South African Reserve Bank repeatedly hiked its lending
rate to save the Rand, commercial banks followed suit. The
country's major banks have raised their prime lending rates three
times since June 11, from 18.25 percent up to about 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mike Schussler, an economist, said: "It was expected that the
weaker Rand and increases in interest rates would knock business
confidence. The biggest problem is if the Asian crisis continues
and drags South Africa and our neighbors along."
</P>
<P>
The country was probably closer to the bottom of the business
cycle than a few months ago, Schussler said, adding that things
would change by the end of the year, with economic growth picking
up and more jobs being created.
</P>
<P>
Sacob maintained its growth forecast for the year at 1.5
percent and inflation at 5.8 percent. The government's growth
target for the year is 2.5 percent, according to the chamber of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
The Sacob's director-general said that he expected speculators
to maintain their attack on the Rand for a few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
