<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Wimbledon finalist de Alvarez dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Three time Wimbledon finalist Lili
de Alvarez died on Wednesday at the age of 93, the Spanish sports
council announced.
</P>
<P>
Alvarez made the Wimbledon women's final on three consecutive
occasions between 1926 and 1928, losing once to Kitty Godfrey and
twice to Helen Wills.
</P>
<P>
Her only major title came in the women's doubles at the 1929
French Open, with Dutch partner Kea Bouman.
</P>
<P>
After tennis, de Alvarez turned her attention to other sports
and she became a Spanish national skiing champion in 1941.
</P>
<P>
De Alvarez was born in Rome and lived much of her early life
in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Her death comes 13 days before she was due to be a guest at
Spain's Federation Cup tie in Madrid against the United States and
receive one of the country's highest sporting honors, the gold
medal for sporting achievement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
