<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Urges Efforts for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
Wednesday called on all political parties of the country to make
efforts in order to achieve peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting here with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem, Weizman said progress in the peace process should be the main
aim of all the parties.
</P>
<P>
"Israel can not allow itself to be so unwise and miss the
chance to achieve peace with the Arab world," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Weizman noted that he has only partially been briefed on the
state of peace negotiations with the Palestinians, but he said he
will probably meet with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
discuss the political situation.
</P>
<P>
Israel is under pressure from the United States and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to accept an American peace
initiative in a bid to break the deadlock in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, which PNA has formally accepted, calls on
Israel to withdraw its troops from 13 percent of the West Bank in
the second redeployment in return for the fulfillment of the
Palestinian commitments to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said on Tuesday that a peace agreement would be
reached in the near future if the PNA took necessary measures to
ensure the security of Israel.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also noted early
this week that the peace process is progressing and the Israeli
government may make a decision on the further redeployment
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
