<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Equal Exploitation of Caspian Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Wednesday reiterated that a legal regime should be formulated for
the Caspian Sea and its littoral states should exploit the
resources on equal bases.
</P>
<P>
Before seeing Turkmen President Saparmurat Niyazov off at the
end of his three-day visit, Khatami said the Caspian Sea belongs
to the littoral states -- Azerbaijan, Iran, Kazakhstan, Russia and
Turkmenistan -- and it should be a place for peace and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov's visit focused on the exploitation of the Caspian
resources, mainly oil, after Kazakhstan and Russia Monday signed
an agreement to divide the northern part of the sea between them.
</P>
<P>
Iran is not opposed to a fair share of the seabed resources by
the littoral states, Khatami said, stressing that any change in
the existing legal regime of the sea must be endorsed by the five
countries.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Kazakh-Russian agreement, Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said on Tuesday that Iran
would not recognize any bilateral agreements aimed at dividing the
Caspian Sea for exploiting its resources.
</P>
<P>
The five nations bordering the world's largest inland water
have been at odds for years over the ownership of the oil and
natural gas in the seabed.
</P>
<P>
The three nations with oil near their coastlines -- Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan -- want the water divided into
national sectors so they can claim the oil for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Russia, two nations with little or no oil near their
Caspian coasts, want equal exploitation of the sea's resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
