<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Difficult to Meet Inflation Target: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The rebasing of the consumer price
index and the subsequent change in the inflation target will make
it more difficult for the Philippine government to meet its
inflation target and perhaps other economic targets set with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
This was the apprehension expressed Wednesday by Central Bank
Governor Gabriel Singson following the adjustment in the inflation
computation which now makes the inflation level much higher.
</P>
<P>
Singson pointed out that the inflation target set under the
Precautionary Arrangement with the IMF used the base year of 1988
and therefore projected an average inflation range this year of
between 7.5 percent and 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the National Statistics Office rebased its inflation
computation in May this year from the year 1988 to 1994 and will
officially use 1994 as the base year starting in August.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that it would be difficult to recompute the figure
earlier submitted to the IMF especially since the central bank
does not normally compute the inflation figures.
</P>
<P>
If the inflation numbers are skewed, Singson added, all other
assumptions for the macroeconomic targets may similarly be
affected and thus prevent the country from meeting its targets.
</P>
<P>
Singson suggested that the statistics office continue to issue
two inflation rates, one based in 1988 and the other using 1994,
until the end of the year so that the central bank can still
verify that it is meeting its targets with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Singson was confident that if the inflation rate still uses the
base year of 1988, the government would still be able to meet its
inflation target set with the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
