<HEADLINE> Chinese Manufacturers' Association Celebrates HK's Handover Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Manufacturers'
Association of Hong Kong (CMA) held a reception here Wednesday to
celebrate the first anniversary of Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and other principal officials of the
SAR government, officials of the institutions of the Central
Government in the SAR, foreign consuls in Hong Kong and leading
figures of the local business community attended the reception.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the function, CMA President Herbert Liang said that
although Hong Kong faces a difficult situation at present due to
the Asian financial crisis, it still retained its solid economic
fundamentals one year after it returned to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Both Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill
Clinton, who visited Hong Kong respectively in the past week,
spoke highly of the achievements Hong Kong had made in the past
year and expressed their confidence in the future development of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
During their visits to Hong Kong, President Jiang assured the
Hong Kong people that the Central Government will provide its full
support to the SAR and President Clinton said Hong Kong will be
among the first economies in the region to recover from the
financial crisis, Liang said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that after a period of adjustment, Hong
Kong will become more competitive, the economy will further
develop on a healthier basis and the adjustment will help Hong
Kong build a more solid economic foundation and put Hong Kong into
a new phase of development in the 21st century.  
</P>
