<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Geologists Claim to Find Smallest Fossil Eggs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Indian geologists claimed to
find for the first time the smallest fossil eggs dating back to
225 million years, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
What makes the finding unique is that the eggs are microscopic,
soft-shelled belonging to the late Gondwana Age, PTI quoted D. P.
Das and P. M. Datta as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fossil eggs of dinosaurs, birds and reptiles collected so far
are large, hard-shelled and two million to 180 million years ago,
belonging to the Pleistocene to the Upper Triassic Era.
</P>
<P>
The nest of eggs discovered from the south Rewa Gondwana Basin
in the central Madhya Pradesh shows remarkable similarity in shape
and structure to recent fish eggs, the two scientists from the
Geological Survey of India in Calcutta reported in the recent
issue of Current Science Journal.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said though the fossil eggs did not show any
specific features, they were similar in structure to fossil eggs
of ampharyngodon mola, a fish of recent times.
</P>
<P>
The new fossil eggs are, however, smaller than ampharyngodon
eggs, according to the geologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
