<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Kill 24 in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 24 people have been killed
and about 400,000 people have had to abandon their homes due to
mud slides and flooding triggered by heavy rains over the past
five days in southeastern Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The deaths were the result of house collapse and mud slides in
the city of Chittagong and the hill districts in the region,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 people have been injured and 20,000 hectares of paddy
fields damaged, they said.
</P>
<P>
"An exact assessment of loss is not possible at this moment,"
Abul Bashar, an agriculture officer said.
</P>
<P>
The rainfall has lessened since Tuesday and the situation is
expected to improve soon, weather officials said.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no further damage if the rainfall stops," they
said.
</P>
<P>
The roads linking Chittagong and the resort town of Cox's
Bazar, and between Chittagong and the hill tracts have been
reportedly cut off as some sections of the roads have gone under
water.
</P>
<P>
An official in Cox's Bazar confirmed the deaths of 12 persons
in his district, saying the figure might go up as reports from
remote areas were not available at present.
</P>
<P>
Low-lying areas in Chittagong, Cox's Bazar and hill districts
of Bandarban, Khagrachari, still remained flooded and thousands of
people were made homeless, a report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
