<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Canadian firms Flock to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's duty-free maquiladora zone
is attracting a growing number of Canadian manufacturers, "The
Globe and Mail" newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Since the North American free-trade agreement took effect in 1994,
the number of Canadian-owned duty-free maquiladora plants has more
than tripled to 30 from nine, and they now employ more than 10,000
Mexicans, according to the survey of Canada's participation in the
Mexican trade scheme.
</P>
<P>
The study by the U.S. International Trade Commission also found that
the vast majority of the companies' products are then exported to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Under the maquiladora plan, companies can import any parts they
need, use cheap Mexican labor to assemble their products and then pay
duty only on the value added in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian plants are heavily concentrated in the automotive,
electronics and textile industries.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 350 Canadian companies in Mexico, but fewer
than 10 percent of those operate under the maquiladora plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Myanmar May Form Joint Special Processing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The private sectors of Bangladesh and
Myanmar have agreed to set up a special processing zone as a joint
venture in Cox's Bazar district in the southeastern part of this
South Asian nation, the national BSS news agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the private sector investors had sought
initiatives from their respective governments in this regard,
President of the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industries (DCCI)
Maksud Khan was quoted by the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for a decision from the governments," he said.
</P>
<P>
A DCCI business promotion delegation during a recent visit to
Myanmar discussed with Myanmar industrialists and businessmen on
measures for expanding bilateral trade and investment, and made
recommendations to governments of the two countries for
implementation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar had a vast reserve of forests -- bamboo and soft timber
for paper and pulp, and mineral resources like limestone and
clinker for cement industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The finished products from the zone would be exported to other
countries including Myanmar to the benefit of both countries,
considering the economic sanctions imposed on Myanmar by some
countries, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is one of Bangladesh's two close neighbors, but trade
between the two countries has remained small in volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
