<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market closed
marginally higher Wednesday as the government-backed takeover of a
local gas distributor Allgas Energy dominated an otherwise
directionless day of trading.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said there were no clear trends guiding trade as the
all ordinaries index closed 4.8 points stronger at 2,774.1.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial Average closed 6.8 points lower
Tuesday night at 9,085.0 but a stronger performance on Asian
markets helped the local market's confidence Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's turnover reached 248.4 million shares, worth 651
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Allgas shares topped the value table with 5.92 million shares
changing hands worth 84 million U.S. dollars as they closed at
1.28 Australian dollars, or just under six percent, higher at
23.00 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Allgas takeover overshadowed a record breaking rise in
Commonwealth Bank of Australia shares Wednesday, which climbed
27.9 Australian cents firmer to 19.97 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other banks were also broadly higher as National Australia Bank
climbed six cents to 22.36 Australian dollars, Westpac bank rose
12 cents to 10.57 Australian dollars and ANZ bank gained one cent
to 11.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The lack of clear direction in the wider market, however, was
evidenced by the evenness of the falling and rising stocks at 507
and 511 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index added 6.5 points to 1,079.7 and the all
industrials index rose 3.5 points to 4,873.2.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were boosted by a resurgent BHP which climbed
28 cents to 14.20 Australian dollars. It indicated Wednesday it
was considering selling its 240 million U.S. dollar power
division.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 7.6 points better at 1,124.5 with the
price of bullion in Sydney trading at 295.30 U.S. dollars an
ounce, up 1.95 U.S. dollars on Tuesday's close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
