<HEADLINE> HK Puts Reclaimed Site to Tourism-Oriented Uses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government announced Wednesday to
grant a piece of reclaimed land to the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA) for temporary uses until 2000.
</P>
<P>
Located on the waterfront of the Victoria Harbor and near the
Central Business District on the Hong Kong Island, the
2.56-hectare former Tamar site was granted under a short-term
tenancy for recreational, entertainment and tourism-oriented and
promotional purposes together with parking of cars for a term up
to June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government received a total of 19 submissions, most of
which proposed the recreational uses. A spokesman for the Lands
Department said Wednesday, "We consider the HKTA, being a statuary
and well-established body, is the most appropriate agent that can
quickly put the site to temporary uses."
</P>
<P>
"The HKTA will be tasked to manage the site and put together a
diversified program for the use of the site throughout the tenancy
period," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The HKTA welcomed the government's decision. "This is a unique
site which offers tremendous opportunities to stage events that
could otherwise not be held in Hong Kong," said HKTA Executive
Director Amy Chan.
</P>
<P>
She continued: "The harbor backdrop and central location make
this an ideal venue for major productions that can attract large
audiences both local and from overseas." The HKTA will lease the
site to suitable event organizers.
</P>
<P>
When the tenancy expires in June 2000, the government will
take back the site for the construction of the new Central
government complex. 
</P>
</TEXT>
