<HEADLINE> HK External Trade Decreases in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
re-exports, domestic exports and imports registered decreases in
May 1998 on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
According to external trade figures for May released by the
Census and Statistics Department Wednesday, the value of total
exports in May (comprising re-exports and domestic exports)
declined to 113.3 billion HK dollars (14.5 billion U.S. dollars),
3.2 percent lower than that of a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the value of re-exports went down by 3.1 percent
to 97 billion HK dollars (12.4 billion U.S. dollars) while that of
domestic exports fell by 3.6 percent to 16.2 billion HK dollars
(2.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of imports dropped by 7.5 percent in May over a year
earlier to 124.5 billion HK dollars (16 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of 11.2 billion HK dollars (1.4 billion
U.S. dollars) was recorded in May, according to the statistics.
This figure was much lower than the 17.5 billion HK dollars (2.24
billion U.S. dollars) for May 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months combined in 1998, the value of total
exports was lower by 2.1 percent over the same period last year,
the statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
A government secretariat spokesman said the export performance
remained slack so far this year partly due to the continued
strength of the U.S. dollar and the reduction in import demand in
Japan as well as in those crisis-hit East Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman noted, exports to a number of other key
markets, including the United States, Britain and Taiwan, should
have registered growth in the first five months taken together.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also pointed out that the visible trade deficit
narrowed considerably in the first five months as the value of
imports was on a distinct decline amidst the consolidation in
domestic demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
