<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Condemns Japan's Experimental Tuna Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Australia Wednesday condemned
Japan's experimental tuna fishing program, warning that Japan was
breaching international law if it went ahead with the plan.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan announced by Japan earlier Wednesday, 65
Japanese vessels will catch up to 1,400 tons of southern bluefin
tuna (SBT) between July 10 and August 31 in the Indian Ocean in a
bid to increase its catch quota.
</P>
<P>
Australian Resources Minister Warwick Parer called in Japanese
Ambassador Yukio Satoh Wednesday morning to condemn Japan's
decision to implement the program.
</P>
<P>
"Japan's decision to go ahead with the experimental fishing
program is shortsighted, and will reduce the chance that the
southern bluefin tuna stock will recover from its present depleted
state," Parer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"We are now considering the formal dispute resolution
mechanisms that are available to press the matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese plan came as the Commission for the Conservation
of Southern Bluefin Tuna (CCSBT) has been deadlocked since a
meeting earlier this year where Australia and New Zealand denied
Japan's request to conduct experimental fishing and to increase
the overall catch quota by 3,000 tons from 11,750 tons.
</P>
<P>
Last year's 11,750 ton quota, which had been kept intact for
the past 10 years, allowed Japan to fish 6,065 tons of tuna,
Australia 5,265 tons and New Zealand 420 tons.
</P>
<P>
Australia has already banned Japanese tuna boats from fishing
in Australia's Exclusive Economic Zone as well as from Australian
ports except in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
"Following the Japanese decision, Australia will continue the
ban and review it on a month-to-month basis," Parer said.
</P>
<P>
Australia, Japan and New Zealand are the founding members of
the CCSBT, an international organization which sets a total
allowable catch and national allocations for member countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abiola's Children Agree on Autopsy, Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Three children of late Nigerian
opposition leader Moshood Abiola have agreed not to bury his body
until full autopsy is carried out, his personal doctor has said.
</P>
<P>
Ore Falomo, personal doctor of Abiola who died Tuesday
afternoon in Nigerian capital Abuja of heart attack, named the
three children as Kola, Deji and Agboola, according to
Wednesday's Guardian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The doctor also said a team of pathologists from Britain and
Canada would arrive in Nigeria within 24 hours to carry out the
autopsy.
</P>
<P>
In a move to convince the opposition of its innocence, the
Nigerian government has ordered an autopsy in the presence of
Abiola's personal doctor, if agreed to by Abiola's family.
</P>
<P>
This means Abiolas' body will not be sent back to Lagos and
buried within 24 hours according to Muslim practices, as it was
indicated earlier.
</P>
<P>
Abiola's sudden death on the eve of his expected release has
aroused suspicions of foul play among his family and the
opposition. His daughter Wura Abiola, who is living in the United
State, said she believed her father was murdered.
</P>
<P>
His death has sparked violence in Lagos and Ibadan cities in
the southwest, the strongholds of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
The violence began Tuesday evening in several parts of Lagos
soon after the news of Abiola's death Tuesday afternoon in Abuja
spread to Lagos, with many of his angry and shocked supporters
taking to the street, attacking cars, shops and burning tyres.
</P>
<P>
A driver told Xinhua he saw hundreds of youths attacking cars
and motorists in the Oshodi area, on his way to the Lagos airport
Tuesday night. He said he saw some people were lying on the
ground, but did not know if they were dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
A foreign businessman who lived in the Ebute-Metta area said
he heard sporadic gunshots outside.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said at least seven people have died.
</P>
<P>
In Ibadan, the capital of Oyo State, youths took to the
street, burning vehicles and chanting songs of protest around
Mokola and Gate areas, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the Presidency said Abiola died of cardiac
arrest at 4:00 p.m. local time Tuesday in the federal capital of
Abuja, when he was having a meeting with visiting United States
Under-Secretary of State Thomas Pickering and Nigerian leader
General Abdulsalam Abubakar in the Aso Rock presidential villa on
his release after four years in jail.
</P>
<P>
According to Pickering, who was speaking to the Cable News
Network Tuesday, Abiola seemed to be clear and lucid in his
statement but mid-way through the meeting, in the early stages,
he (Abiola) had to restore his thought, took some tea and had
trouble in breathing and then went into toilet.
</P>
<P>
"He came out obviously distressed and asked for cough medicine
and pain killer and sat on the couch and was overheated. He
removed his shirt and asked that the room be ventilated and
generally declined from there," he said.
</P>
<P>
In about seven to 10 minutes, Pickering said, a doctor was
called in and said the man was very ill and had to be admitted to
hospital immediately, upon which Abiola was rushed to the clinic
in the presidency.
</P>
<P>
"They (the doctors) worked for over an hour and a half in all
conceivable way... to save his life but unfortunately at the end
of their efforts it was not possible and he died," Pickering
said.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, the politician-businessman, was widely believed to be
winner of the June 12, 1993 presidential elections. His release
has been seen as of crucial importance to the military
government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
Last week, visiting United Nations (UN) Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and his Commonwealth counterpart Emeka Anyaoku said the
military government had agreed to free him very soon, along with
all the other political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who held a private talk with Abiola, said the man
looked hearty and healthy.
</P>
<P>
Some pictures Anyaoku exhibited to newsmen at a press
conference here a week ago showed a smiling Abiola who looked to
be in good health.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government was expected to announce Abiola's
release any time from Wednesday at the end of the one-month
national mourning for the late head of state, General Sani Abacha
who died suddenly on June 8.
</P>
<P>
His family in Lagos have been expecting his release in the
last month since Abacha's death following the release of some
political detainees by new leader Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
In a rapid reaction to Abiola's death, the U.N. chief has
extended his condolence to the Abiola family and urged the
military government to make good on its pledge to release all
remaining political detainees and to define a credible process
for the democratic transition to civilian rule within a
reasonable time frame.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Provisional Ruling Council and the National Council
of States are expected to meet Wednesday in Abuja, at the end of
which a transition timetable is expected to be announced, after
one-month long of intensive consultations by the government
involving all sectors of the home society as well as the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Ever since Abacha's death, Abiola's supporters have been
demanding for the cancellation of Abacha's transition program,
which is expected to usher in an elected civilian government in
October. Instead, they want a national unity government to be
headed by Abiola.
</P>
<P>
Now with Abiola passing away, the only thing that could be
expected from the Abubakar government is the extension of the
transition program from six to one year, as has been canvassed by
some groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
