<HEADLINE> Paris Will Maintain Control of Tower Eiffel: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The French Minister of Economy and
Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn said Wednesday that Paris will
maintain the control of Tower Eiffel instead of selling it to
Americans which will buy a French bank that owns the stocks of
the tourism business from the tower.
</P>
<P>
The French government plans to sell the public insurance bank
Credit Foncier de France (CFF) to the GMAC insurance company of
the United States, which manages the pension fund of the General
Motors, and Texas billionaire Robert Bass.
</P>
<P>
The CFF owns 50 percent of the stocks of tourism business from
Tower Eiffel.
</P>
<P>
The expected take-over of CFF by GMAC and Bass have triggered
fear among some Paris council deputies that the tower will be
also sold to the Americans, who they said could take it to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In response to the worry of the deputies, Strauss-Kahn said in
a communique that this monument is "imprescriptible and
inalienable" from Paris.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn said that Paris has the full freedom to choose
other companies to run the tourism business of Tower Eiffel after
CFF changes hands in mid-July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
