<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Vows to Carry Out Permanent Tax Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said Wednesday his government will carry out permanent
income tax cuts in 1999 in an effort to shore up the sluggish
Japanese economy, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning tax system reform, We would like to implement
(permanent) tax cuts, starting next year, that will be supported
by the public," Hashimoto told a press conference in Nagoya,
central Japan.
</P>
<P>
Permanent income tax cuts are expected to spur consumer
spending, which accounts for about 60 percent of Japan's gross
domestic product (GDP), and to help spark an economic rebound.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto made the statement after his vacillation on permanent
income tax cuts over the past several days drew attacks from
within his Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto apparently decided to make his policy line clear in a
bid to woo voters in Sunday's election for the House of
Councillors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveys forecast that the LDP will unlikely realize its
nine-year aspiration of recapturing a majority in the upper
chamber and might even fail to retain the 61 LDP seats being
contested in the race due to the country's slow economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
