<HEADLINE> South Africa Expresses Shock at Abiola's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South African officials
Wednesday expressed shock and sadness at the death of detained
Nigerian politician Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, Nigeria's foremost opposition political figure who
spent the past four years in jail, died of an apparent heart
attack while in a meeting with Nigerian and United States
officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela expressed his "deep shock" at
Abiola's death. Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana said the
South African government was trying to get more information from
the Nigerian authorities about Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
"We are unable to make a comprehensive statement at this
stage, but there is no doubt that Abiola was a critical factor in
propelling Nigeria to democracy," Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, 60, was "taken ill during a meeting which was being
held by Nigerian and United States officials with him," said a
statement from the chief press secretary to Nigerian leader
General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry also expressed shock and regret
at Abiola's death.
</P>
<P>
"We think he could have played an important role in Nigerian
domestic politics," spokesman Machiel van Niekerk said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress (ANC) said it was
unfortunate that the Nigerian military government had not seen
fit to release Abiola, a millionaire businessman.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, ANC secretary general Kgalema Motlanthe said:
"Yet we express our hope that Nigerian ruler General Abdulsalam
Abubakar and the Nigerian people will utilize this tragic
incident to forge ahead with speedy preparations for a democratic
election."  
</P>
