<HEADLINE> Fires Kill 54 Ugandans in First Half of 1998 in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-four people have been killed
in more than 140 fire outbreaks in the Ugandan capital Kampala
and its suburbs in the first six months of 1998, a report from
the fire station has said.
</P>
<P>
The undated report carried in Wednesday's New Vision daily
said January and June top the list of fire incidences, with 30
and 28 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Mugisa, the chief fire officer, was quoted as
attributing the frequent fire outbreaks to the dry season and
unattended burning candles in residences.
</P>
<P>
Unclear reporting to the fire station is the main cause to the
bulk of destruction, he added.
</P>
<P>
"When a fire breaks out, people try to stop it. When things
run out of hand, then they approach us," he said, "most of the
calls were from the suburbs of Nakulabye, Kibuli, Nsambya,
Kasubi, Olda Kampala, Kawempe and Rubaga where communication is
poorest."
</P>
<P>
The report revealed that 21 people were rescued from sewers,
pits, lifts, buildings and car wreckages.
</P>
<P>
The fire officer also advised people not to invest huge
amounts of money in vulnerable makeshift structures which easily
catch fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
