<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian Rebels Kill Civilians despite Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 8 (Xinhua) - As the second round of peace
talks for all Burundian warring parties is approaching, there are
still reports of rebels' killing of civilians and refugees
fleeing into neighboring Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said Wednesday that at least 19
Burundians were killed last week in two separate rebel attacks
and governmental counter-attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi government and all the political parties as well
as rebel groups promised a ceasefire during their first round of
peace talks last month in Arusha, north Tanzania, and agreed to
resume the talks on July 20.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted an army spokesman as saying Tuesday that
rebels killed five civilians in a village some 100 kilometers
south of the capital Bujumbura, burning 15 houses before the
government forces intervened and killing about ten rebels.
</P>
<P>
Four other civilians were killed when their mini-bus was
ambushed by suspected rebels on a main road south of Bujumbura
along Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR)in Kigoma, west Tanzania, said some 20 to 30
Burundian refugees entered Tanzania daily.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them are uncertain about the truce. They fear of
being killed," a UNHCR official said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a UNHCR report said that as of April 30 this year,
Tanzania accommodates in its western regions a total of 328,737
refugees from neighbouring Democratic Republic of Congo, Burundi,
Rwanda and Somalia, 80 percent of whom are Burundians.
</P>
<P>
Only some 2,000 Burundian refugees have returned home since
Pieere Buyoya took power following a coup in July 1996 which
incurred the economic sanctions by the Great Lakes nations.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 Burundians, mostly civilians, were
reportedly killed since Melchior Ndadaye, first president elected
under a multi-party system, was killed in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
