<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soldiers Play Vital Role in Combating Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 100,000 officers and
soldiers from the People's Liberation Army (PLA) and armed police
units stationed in eastern, central and southern parts of China
are joining local militiamen to battle heavy flooding and provide
emergency relief.
</P>
<P>
Consecutive days of heavy rain have caused flooding in the
lower and middle of the Yangtze River, the nation's longest
river, and the Pearl River in south China, as well as numerous
other smaller rivers across the country.
</P>
<P>
Today's edition of People's Daily reported that rapid-response
brigades and emergency units formed by soldiers and local
militiamen in central China's Hubei Province rescued more than
15,000 local residents besieged by flooding, transferred more than
1,000 tons of materials and goods and reinforced dikes stretching
500 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding along the Xiangjiang River and its tributaries
in late June ceded, with soldiers and militiamen in neighboring
Hunan Province rushing to repair some 8,700 heavily damaged areas
in preparation for the possibility of new floods.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers in Jiujiang, a popular scenic city in east China's
Jiangxi Province, and local militiamen are patrolling the Yong'an
Dike along the Yangtze River to guard against and prevent any
possible new breaches.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, armed police units in county level areas in Jiangsu,
Anhui, Zhejiang provinces have established emergency command
centers and over 2,000 teams to respond to emergencies.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 PLA soliders from the Guangzhou Military
Command and members of naval and air force units have also join in
battling flooding on four local rivers. The units have rescued
250,000 people, reinforced 168 km of dikes and handled 2.6 million
tons of goods and materials. Naval units used sandbags to repair
and reinforce a 16 km stretch of an embankment along the Xunjiang
River in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, units of the armed forces have sent medical teams to
flooded areas to provide prompt medical care, distribute medicines
and prevent outbreaks of epidemic diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
