<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Ready to End Instability in S. Asia: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is ready for talks to
end the situation of instability and insecurity in South Asia,
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's special envoy Akram Zaki
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Zaki said India's nuclear tests
on May 11 and 13 were a "clear breach" of the international law
and an "act of provocation."
</P>
<P>
After carefully examining the situation, his country conducted
nuclear tests for self-defense on May 28 and 30, he said. "There
was no any alternative for this."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan has declared an unilateral moratorium on
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Zaki is in Nepal on a mission to brief the Nepali leaders on
his country's perception of the current situation in South Asia
after the nuke tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He earlier handed over a letter from Sharif to Nepali Prime
Minister Girija Prasad Koirala and met with other Nepali leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Nepalese leaders are very much worried about the nuclear
tests, but they agreed that there is a regional balance," Zaki
told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
"It will help to understand the gravity of the situation and
resolve the crisis," he added.
</P>
<P>
He refused to disclose the contents of the letter. "The postman
has no right to read the letter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Foreign Ministry has said the letter covered matters
of strengthening regional stability.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy said Sharif attaches great importance to
peace and stability and gives top priority to economic cooperation
in South Asia as it is inhabited by most of the poor people in the
world.
</P>
<P>
"The Kashmir dispute has created difficulties in giving
concentration on economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zaki stressed that the Kashmir issue should be resolved through
discussions and that Pakistan is ready for third-party mediation
to help resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have fought three wars since their
independence in 1947 and two of them were over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
India has ruled out any outside mediation in its dispute with
Pakistan, including that by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
On the economic sanctions imposed by the international
community on Pakistan after its nuclear tests, Zaki said, "It may
damage psychologically, but the nation is ready to face it."
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to leave for Bangladesh Wednesday after
concluding a five-day visit to Nepal. He will also visit Sri Lanka
and the Maldives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
