<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The signing on Monday by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Kazakh counterpart Nursultan Nazarbayev of an agreement on
sharing the oil resources of the northern part of the Caspian Sea
will trigger a dominant politico-economic battle for years to
come. Former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski
even predicts that the Caspian and Central Asia region would
become a new "axis of the world" because of their tremendously
rich oil resources.
</P>
<P>
-- Day after day, the question of Kosovo is becoming more and
more inextricable. The Western powers meeting on Wednesday in Bonn
are faced with increasing difficulty as for what measures to take
to solve the crisis. The European capitals and Washington are
fully aware of the potential devastating consequences of the
Kosovo conflict, as it risks to spread to other countries of the
region, especially Macedonia, where live a great Albanian
community.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The stock exchange markets of Western countries continue to
benefit from the capitals flowing from Asia, where the economic
and financial situation remains unstable. Paris beat its 45th
record in stock index on Tuesday since the beginning of the year,
with its stock index CAC 40 attaining 4,333.09 points.
</P>
<P>
-- The prices of old houses in Paris rose by 1.5 percent in the
first three months of 1998, as compared with the same quarter last
year. This is the first rise of prices of real estate properties
in the capital in seven years. The average price of old real
estates in Paris now stands at 15,277 francs (2,546 U.S. dollars)
one square meter. 
</P>
