<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Expels Russian Diplomat in Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korean announced Wednesday the
expulsion of a diplomat of the Russian Embassy here in retaliation
for Moscow's deportation of a South Korean diplomat on alleged
espionage activities last weekend.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade Sun
Joun-yung called in Valeri Suhinin, a minister-counsellor of the
Russian Embassy in Seoul, and told him that the South Korean
government has decided to evict Oleg Abramkin, a counsellor of
the Russian Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
The decision came just one day after Counsellor Cho Sung-woo of
the South Korean Embassy in Moscow returned here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Affairs Ministry last Saturday declared Cho
"persona non grata" and ordered him to leave Russia within 72
hours after detaining and questioning him for hours on espionage
charge last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cho was accused of having engaged in espionage activity by the
Russian Federal Security Service as a Russian Foreign Ministry
official named Valetin Moiseyev was arrested when he was supplying
"confidential information" to Cho.
</P>
<P>
"I am not ashamed of what I did as a diplomat. I think the
Russian government expelled me because it regarded me as
unfriendly, " Cho said upon arrival at Seoul Kimpo International
Airport on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Monday, South Korea protested at the Russian expulsion of Cho,
saying that Russia's detaining of Cho for hours of questioning
last Friday violated the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations.
</P>
<P>
The expulsions are the first diplomatic fray in the relations
between the two nations since they set up diplomatic ties in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legendary Chinese Woman Artist Sets up Foundation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A young talented Chinese woman
calligrapher and painter set up a 10-million-yuan (1.2 million
U.S. dollars) foundation here today as part of her effort to
develop China's arts education.
</P>
<P>
Lou Zhenggang, 32, is perhaps the richest young artist in her
circle. As the daughter of an ordinary worker, she established her
name at the age of 12 when she was sent to Beijing's Central
Academy of Fine Arts as an unusually talented child.
</P>
<P>
When she was 22, one of her works sold for 400,000 U.S. dollars
on the Japanese market. Lou now resides in Japan and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The successful artist was a guest of Boutros-Boutros Ghali,
former secretary general of the United Nations, and dozens of
Chinese top leaders.
</P>
<P>
There have been debates in China on her success, with many
people describing her as the proof of the theory of innate
genius. However, Lou attributed her success to hard work, and said
that is why she decided to set up the foundation, which aims to
serve young artists who have few opportunities to receive art
training.
</P>
<P>
The Grace Z.G. Lou Arts Education Development Fund will be
jointly managed by the Ministry of Education and Lou herself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Assures Support for Philippine Air Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Ejercito Estrada
Wednesday vowed to provide the Philippine Air Force with modern
equipment and facilities to effectively pursue its military and
socio-civic missions, especially in protecting the environment and
making rescues in disasters.
</P>
<P>
"I assure you that you will have the planes, weapons and
equipment that will match your competence, patriotism and
courage," Estrada said in his speech at the air force's 51st
anniversary at Villamor Air Base in Manila.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the country now enjoys peace and stability
the air force is expected to help in nation-building and
development, especially in environmental protection and disaster
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
Estrada urged the air force to further strengthen its civil
defense capability in anticipation of the coming typhoon season.
Toward this end, he revealed his plan to expand the air force's
search and rescue missions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also vowed to intensify the air force's relief
and rehabilitation programs and civic and mercy missions with the
help of various government agencies to deliver goods and services
to disaster areas as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We must always alleviate promptly the ill-effects of
calamities to our masses. Similarly, we must harness your
capability for speedy humanitarian action, including emergency
medical evacuations and delivery of health services in remote
areas," Estrada said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
