<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Welcomes U.N. Resolution to Upgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo-based Arab League (AL) has
welcomed a resolution adopted by the United Nations General
Assembly on upgrading the Palestinian status in the world
organization.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation Arab organization expressed hope on Tuesday that
the resolution would be followed by similar steps to bring a just
and comprehensive peace to the Middle East, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency (MENA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly approved an Arab-sponsored resolution
on Tuesday to upgrade the status of the Palestine Liberation
Organization from an observer to that of a near statehood.
</P>
<P>
The voting was 124 in favor, four against with 10
abstentions. Israel, the United States, and the Marshall Islands
and Micronesia, two Pacific island countries, voted against the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution is "the most important step" to support the
Palestinian stance on the Israeli intransigence, AL Assistant
Secretary General Mohab Moqbel told MENA.
</P>
<P>
He said the AL will continue contacts and coordination with its
members and the international community to give impetus to the
Palestinian stand.
</P>
<P>
Saeed Kamal, AL assistant secretary general for Palestine's
affairs, said the resolution is an international message to the
Israeli government in the first place that came just in time.
</P>
<P>
The resolution conforms with the international will towards
recognizing the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people and
the support for the Palestinian struggle for resuming the peace
process under the land-for-peace principle, Kamal said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian permanent representative to the AL
Mohamad Sobeih voiced welcome to the U.N. General Assembly
resolution.
</P>
<P>
"It affirms the Palestinians' right to establish an
independent state, with Jerusalem as its capital," Sobeih said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tinajin to Expand Import-Exports Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- North China's Tianjin municipality
plans to expand foreign trade in 1998 in order to achieve an
import and export volume of 10 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vice Mayor Wang Shuzu said the city is both a major
trade center and important foreign trade port in north China.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin exported products valued at 5.02 billion US dollars
in 1997, up 23.9 percent on the previous year, with its import
volume growing by 17.8 percent to 5.01 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city, which has thousands of enterprises engaged in foreign
trade, announced a list of its top 50 foreign trade companies
earlier this year. Of these companies, eight have annual exports
of over 100 million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The top 50 enterprises had exports of 3.58 billion US dollars,
or 71.3 percent of the municipality's total export volume.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises, which account for close to one
third of the 50 firms, accounted for over half of the city's total
exports. Motorola ranks first amongst related firms with annual
exports of some 100 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city expects rapid foreign trade development this year and
has adopted a series of preferential policies to encourage related
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
