<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Introduce Pollution-free Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have introduced
a new pollution-free pesticide which extensive testing reveals is
safe for the environment, crops, human beings and animals.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology recently organized a
meeting in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu
Province, to promote the new product.
</P>
<P>
The pesticide -- Jingyebao -- was jointly developed in 1996 by
the Yuzhong County Pesticide Plant, Northwest China Agricultural
University and the Gansu Academy of Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The pollution-free nonchemical fertilizer leaves no poisonous
residue and is thus friendly to the environment, according to
agronomists. They also noted that the product is especially
effective for battling drug-resistant insects and reduces costs by
as much as 30 percent per hectare.
</P>
<P>
Agronomists said the environmentally-friendly pesticide, which
is made from nicotine in leaf tobacco, will serve as a replacement
for chemical fertilizers in the next century. They also noted that
Yuzhong County produces more than 40,000 tons of leaf tobacco
annually.
</P>
<P>
Only a small portion of the 2.8 million tons of pesticides used
in China each year reach international standards.
</P>
<P>
Recent tests conducted by the Chinese Academy of Sciences
revealed that poisonous residue levels for Jingyebao are
substantially lower than permissible levels. "Widespread
applications of the pesticide will contribute greatly to health
care protection," according to Dr. Liu Xinghai from the Ministry
of Agriculture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
