<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Large Oilfields in Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China is speeding up exploration of
two large oilfields in the central Bohai Sea in an effort to
achieve an annual crude production capacity of 4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Shaodong, chief executive officier of the
China Offshore Oil Bohai Corp (COOBC), oil from the two oilfields
-- Qinhuangdao 32-6 and Nanbao 35-2, will be piped inland through
the port of Jingtang in Tangshan City in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield, with 170 million tons of verified
geological oil reserves, is 100 kilometers east of
Tianjin. Eleven wells have already been drilled there.
</P>
<P>
Nanbao 35-2 Oilfield lies 20 kilometers south of
Tangshan. Four test-wells have been drilled and geological
reserves of 70 million tons have been identified. Nanbao's
reserves have been estimated at 110 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the distance between the two oilfields
is only 20 kilometers, making it possible for their joint
development in a 70-sq km oil-bearing area in the Bohai
Sea.
</P>
<P>
He said that seven standard platforms will be erected in the
two oilfields, two pipelines will be laid at the seabed to
transport oil inland, and terminals will be built in the Port of
Jingtang.
</P>
<P>
Also, requisition of 650 meters of coastline will be made for
building oil transport berths. The entire construction project
will cost 7.29 billion yuan, he added.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Qinhuangdao 32-6 Oilfield will
begin production in 2003 and Nanbao one year later. By 2004, the
two oilfields are expected to produce four million tons of oil a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
