<HEADLINE> Kenya Calls to Curb Trade Imbalance with Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph
Kamotho has urged to narrow the east African country's three
billion Shilling (50.8 million U.S. Dollars) trade imbalance with
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Kenya imports goods worth five billion Shillings (84.7 million
Dollars) from Italy and exports to the European state goods worth
only two billion Shillings (33.9 million Dollars), he was quoted
by Wednesday's media as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Trade between the two countries is low and we would like to
see it increase because if trade and investment grow, we will
rely less on aid," he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Italy to offer more support to small-scale
enterprises in Kenya and use its position in the Group of Seven
and in the European Union to help Kenya expand trade in the
developed world.
</P>
<P>
"Promotion of small-scale enterprises is the only remaining
hope for Kenya," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya receives around 50,000 Italian tourists annually and
many Italians have invested in hotels in Malindi, a famous Indian
Ocean resort located in western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement on promotion and
protection of investment last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
