<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Rising in Tokyo on Tax Cut Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices continued rising in
Tokyo Wednesday on heightened expectations that Japan will cut
income taxes permanently next year to stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange climbed 114.69 points, or 0.70
percent, from Tuesday's close to finish at 16,530.97.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 3.59 points or 0.28 percent to
1,268.40.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 500 million
shares, down from Tuesday's 544.54 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
A morning news report that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto might give details about the tax cuts later in the day
spurred early buying in a wide range of issues, trader said.
</P>
<P>
At one point the key index surged by nearly 220 points. But
the Nikkei's rise fizzled in the afternoon due to selling pressure
as well as continued unwinding of cross-held shares among Japanese
corporations, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers 653 to 510, with 125 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
