<HEADLINE> Philippine President Declares War Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Ejercito
Estrada Wednesday reiterated that peace and order will continue to
be a priority under his administration to ensure that the country
will be an investment hub for local and foreign businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada ordered Philippine National Police Director
General Roberto Lastimoso to restore peace and order and break the
backbone of crime syndicates in the country within six months.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered Lastimoso to prosecute a "big fish" in the
first 100 days of his administration.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping and other crimes are common in the Philippines. Last
year a total of 147 kidnapping cases occurred in the country with
241 people taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the economy can not flourish if crime gangs rule
the streets and sow terror with impunity, scaring away investors.
</P>
<P>
Before assuming the presidency on June 30 this year, Estrada,
as vice president, once chaired the Presidential Anti-Crime
Commission and scored a number of successes in combating kidnapper
and bank robber gangs. 
