<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Child Feeding Program Urges for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Child Supplementary
Feeding Program (CSFP) urgently requires 5.5 million U.S. Dollars
to restock its depleted reserves and save from collapse the
government scheme under which 400,000 children receive food
monthly.
</P>
<P>
Failure to raise the funds immediately will jeopardise efforts
by the Ministry of Health and Child Welfare to control cases of
severe malnutrition in children, particularly in the drought-hit
areas, The Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Maize-meal and cooking oil, the main food components of the
program, have already run out, the CSFP said.
</P>
<P>
The CSFP has already presented the matter to the national
drought relief committee in the Ministry of Public Service, Labor
and Social Welfare to source the required funds from the
government.
</P>
<P>
The CSFP headquarters in Harare Tuesday confirmed the food
shortage and said it was worried that donors would only consider
assistance if the shortage was declared a national disaster.
</P>
<P>
The number of beneficiaries fluctuated over the years with
about one million children under the program at one point. This
had dropped to 300,000 during good seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
