<HEADLINE> S. African Post Office Workers Strike for Wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South African post office
workers are starting a nationwide strike Wednesday after a
dispute over wages, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The three-day industrial action of 40,000 employees threatens
to ground essential telephone and postal services throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
The South African Post Office raised its concern Tuesday about
the strike, saying it would worsen the company's financial
situation and have a negative effect on customer service.
</P>
<P>
"The Post Office's delivery standards have improved
considerably and more than 90 percent national mail is being
delivered on time. A one-day strike could cause a drop of 2.5
percent in that month's delivery standards," the company said.
</P>
<P>
While the Post Office requested all employees to seriously
consider the consequences of participating in strike action,
unions threatened that should the Post Office and Telkom, a
cellular phone service, fail to meet their demands during the
three-day protest, they would embark on a nationwide full-blown
strike. 
</P>
