<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Connect Large Power Grids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Almost all of the power grids in
China will be interconnected before 2020 to allow power exchanges
nationwide, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
The fast-growing economy has brought a new stage in power
development characterized by large capacity and large grids, said
Huo Ji'an, deputy general manager of the State Power Grid
Development Co. Ltd. China now has six inter-provincial power grids
and a group of provincial ones, with 567,000 kilometers of
transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Power Station will create favorable
conditions for the interconnection of power grids nationwide. It
will provide power for the grids in Central, North China and in
Sichuan province and help form the Great Central China Power
Grid, spanning a distance of 2,000 kilometers from east to
west. The grid will also serve as a link to the North, Northwest,
and South grids, Huo said.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, a framework of various inter-provincial grids will
take shape, involving completion of two grids of 500 and 330
kilovolts.
</P>
<P>
Huo said that the Three Gorges Power Station will be completed
by 2009, and a 500-kilovolt project ranging from there to the
Central, North and Sichuan power grids will be established with
9,100 kilometers of direct and alternating current transmission
lines.
</P>
<P>
Thermal-power production bases in Shanxi, Shaanxi and Jiangxi
provinces will ensure large power supplies for Beijing, Tianjin,
Tangshan, Baoding cities in north China and some cities in
northeast China, Huo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
