<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Host World Drama Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- From Canada to Ghana, Australia to
America, hundreds of artists, actors and dancers are expected to
attend the third International Drama Theater and Education
Congress (IDEA) to open Thursday in Kisumu, western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
For 10 days, the town ashore Lake Victoria will be brightened
up by what is billed as the biggest theatrical event in Kenya,
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that such a world congress will be held
in a developing country since the IDEA's inception in Portugal in
1992, said the congress's organizer Opiyo Mumma.
</P>
<P>
Invigorating dances, plays and songs will be the hallmark of
the fete, in which about 80 countries are participating.
Thousands of Kenyan youths will be also involved in theater
visits, performance, educational and cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme for the drama congress set to end on July 19
will be "the Role of Drama, Theater and Education in Locating Our
Space in the New Millennium," said Mumma.
</P>
<P>
Croatian dramatist Vlado Kruzic, Swedish drama pedagogue Anita
Grunbaum, British Prof. David Best and Russian Prof. Sergei
Tcherkaski are among the Thespians set to give keynote addresses.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss the role of theater and drama in
establishing personal and cultural identity and how drama and
theater tackle the cultural, artistic and educational needs of
children and young people in the contemporary world.
</P>
<P>
The second IDEA World Congress was held in Brisbane, Australia
in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
