<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe, Chiluba on Renewed Angolan Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
and his Zambian counterpart Frederick Chiluba expressed concern
about the resurgence of conflict in Angola saying there was need
for a speedy solution to be found to guard against renewed
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said Tuesday night there was need for Chiluba, who
engineered the Lusaka protocol, signed between the ruling
Movement for People's Liberation of Angola (MPLA) party and
opposition National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) movement to revisit the issue to try and establish the
problem resulting in the renewal of the conflict, the Daily
Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lusaka protocol brought normalcy to the war-torn country that
had been rocked by a civil war for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
"It would be good if President Chiluba once again revisited
the protocol and get in touch with Savimbi and President Eduardo
dos Santos and try to read from him (Savimbi) what he says and
what his feelings are and what the problem is," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to see any resort to fighting, to guns, the
people of Angola have had enough of dying and suffering," he
said, "they must go ahead with reconstruction and we want peace
and stability."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said, "all of us were surprised that there were still
conflicts, a solution to the problem in Angola has to be found...
this (the conflict) is simply because of bad behavior on the part
of Savimbi."
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president, who arrived in Zimbabwe aboard a
British Airways Boeing 747 400 plane and held private talks with
Mugabe at Harare airport, was on transit to London.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba added the two leaders also discussed the Eritrean and
Ethiopian border issue and the Organisation of African Unity's
efforts to bring peace between the warring countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are glad that guns are silent for the moment because of
the trip in which President Robert Mugabe was recently involved,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
