<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, Botswana Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The seventh session of the
Zimbabwe/Botswana Joint Commission for Economic Cooperation ended
in Harare Tuesday with the two countries signing a cultural
agreement to extend areas of mutual interest, the Daily Herald
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Issues covered in the cultural agreement include trade,
finance, agriculture, transport, tourism, mining, education and
culture to which the commission urged speedy implementation of
all the agreements and bilateral programs the two countries have
committed themselves.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen cooperation between the two countries further,
three draft proposals were submitted. These are memorandum of
understanding on economic and technical cooperation in the mining
sector, agreement on the promotion and protection of investment,
and road transport agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both governments noted with satisfaction that trade had
significantly increased.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Minister of Foreign Affairs Stan Mudenge said
market liberalization that has been put in place over the years
has helped to narrow the gap in the balance of trade, which had
consistently been in Zimbabwe's favor.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we have agreed to consult on a regular basis, to
examine issues that may hinder the development of an equitable
and just trading relationship between Zimbabwe and Botswana."
</P>
<P>
Botswana's Minister of Foreign Affairs Mompatis Merafhe
praised the decision by Zimbabwe to lift the ban on imports of
petroleum products through the Plumtree Corridor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
