<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia's Ruling Golkar Reforms for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to keep its long-time
political dominance by winning the general elections scheduled for
next May, Indonesia's ruling Golkar (Functional Group) will
convene an extraordinary congress here this week to carry out
important restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The congress to be held from Thursday to Saturday has been
described by the local press as an important event in Golkar's
history and is expected to set out a new format for the party's
organizational structure.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters here Tuesday, chairman of the
extraordinary congress organizing committee Waskito Reksosoedirdjo
revealed that significant changes would be made in Golkar's
policy-making and advisory councils.
</P>
<P>
"We will include the abolition of Golkar's board of patrons,
board of advisors and board of councilors on the agenda of the
extraordinary congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is part of our commitment to total reformation," he said,
adding that the three bodies have such enormous power including
the authority to freeze Golkar's executive board.
</P>
<P>
Based on current Golkar rules and regulations, the board of
patrons headed by former President Soeharto has extensive
authority and the right to annul policies adopted by the head of
the Golkar executive board. Soeharto resigned on May 21 amid
strong public pressure calling for political reforms.
</P>
<P>
The veto right of the board of patrons means that even though
he has stepped down from the presidency, Soeharto still wields
considerable power over the organization.
</P>
<P>
Waskito said there were several options for replacing the board
of patrons, including the establishment of a new board with a
limited advisory role or the removal of the board of patrons' veto
rights.
</P>
<P>
Golkar members and analysts here believe that the upcoming
congress marks a turning point in the evolution of the
organization, particularly in its efforts to become more
independent from the Armed Forces (ABRI). For most of the
country's nearly 53 years of independence, the military has played
an important role in political life.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a congress of the Muhammadiyah Youth organization
last Friday, Minister of Defense and Security and ABRI Commander
General Wiranto said ABRI would be ready to forsake its
influential role in Golkar.
</P>
<P>
Election of Golkar's new chairman is another important item on
the agenda of the upcoming congress which was advanced from a
proposed October date. Several candidates have been proposed by
various sections to replace the current chairman, Harmoko.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Indonesian Retired Military Officers Union
Association and former Vice President Try Sutrisno told reporters
Tuesday that former Defense Minister Edi Sudradjat meets the
criteria for election as the new chairman.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Sudradjat, who has obtained support from
retired generals and other Golkar cadres, appears as the strongest
candidate in the field, followed by Minister/Secretary of State
Akbar Tanjung, Yogyakarta Sultan Sri Hamengku Buwono X and
Manpower Minister Fahmi Idris.
</P>
<P>
Golkar was established in 1964 as an amalgamation of seven
organizations which include the armed forces, labor organizations
and cooperative movements. It has been a dominant political
organization in nearly three decades. The organization, which won
all the seven general elections in the past, grabbed 325 of the
425 seats up for election in the House of Representatives in the
May general elections last year.
</P>
<P>
But local press reports said Golkar will face a big challenge
in next year's general elections which will be contested by more
political parties.
</P>
<P>
"If Golkar can remain united and re-direct its energies away
from the personal enrichment that has so soured its image, it
retains a chance of grabbing a majority of votes at any poll," the
Indonesian Observer commented.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's highest legal body, the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR), will convene an extraordinary meeting on November
10 this year to set the date for next May's general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
