<HEADLINE> Indian Exports Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Indian exports fell sharply in
the first two months of the current financial year beginning April
1, while imports went up by 9.71 percent, resulting in a trade
deficit of around 1.85 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures released Tuesday, exports in
April and May are estimated at 4.994 billion U.S. dollars as
against 5.401 billion dollars in the previous corresponding
period, representing a fall of 7.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is noticeable that exports for May, when India conducted
nuclear tests, dropped to 2.369 billion U.S. dollars compared with
2.862 billion dollars a year earlier, down by 17.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, due to a sharp depreciation of the Indian currency,
exports in rupee terms registered a 3.4 percent increase during
the two months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports in April-May amounted to 6.850 billion
dollars as against 6.243 billion dollars a year earlier, an
increase of 9.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
Faced with this situation, Commerce Minister Rama Krishna Hegde
held an emergency meeting with Finance Minister Yashwant Singh
Tuesday to work out a package of measures to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
The sectors which are expected to be targeted for increasing
exports are the worst-hit areas like electronics hardware, cotton
yarn and food processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
