<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke - Antarctica Experiences Warmest Winter in 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Antarctica experienced a warm winter
with showers, instead of the usual snowfalls, in its coldest
month of June this year, a Polish scientist said.
</P>
<P>
Professor S.R-Suszczewski, a researcher in the biological
institute of the Polish Academy of Sciences, said this winter in
Antarctica was the warmest since 1977, the Polish Press Agency
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Polish observation station in Antarctica measured a record
high of 9 degrees above zero centigrade in June, the scientist
said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout June and in early July, the temperature stayed above
zero, bringing down warm rains and thus creating water ponds on
melting glaciers.
</P>
<P>
Only on July 4, a mild winter appeared with strong wind and
snowfall, and temperature fell to 6.5 degrees centigrade below
zero.
</P>
<P>
Researchers attributed the warm winter to the worsening El Nino
weather phenomenon, which brought abnormal conditions to a vast
area ranging from Antarctica to Alaska in North America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
