<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's State Records Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Sarawak, Malaysia's largest
state, recorded a trade surplus of 5.99 billion ringgit (1.46
billion U.S. dollars) in the first five months of this year,
according to the state's Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 44 percent rise over 4.155 billion
ringgit (one billion U.S. dollars) during the corresponding period
last year, showed the preliminary figures released Wednesday by
the department.
</P>
<P>
During January-May, the total exports stood at 9.651 billion
ringgit (2.353 billion dollars), a 41 percent increase, while
imports were worth 3.662 billion ringgit (893 million dollars), a
fall of 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) remained its largest export item in
value, netting 3.815 billion ringgit (930 million dollars) or 40
percent of the total exports during January-May.
</P>
<P>
The department said the 41 percent higher export receipts were
solely realized through the higher currency exchange rate during
the period.
</P>
<P>
Crude petroleum was the second largest revenue earner, netting
1.662 billion ringgit (405 million dollars) or 17 percent of
Sarawak's total exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the department, 87 percent of Sarawak's exports
during the period were channeled directly to foreign countries and
the rest to Peninsular Malaysia and Sabah in the form of
inter-regional trade.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and transport equipment accounted for 39 percent of
the state's total imports, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
