<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Banning Inland Shrimp Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has endorsed a
resolution of the National Environment Board (NEB) banning inland
shrimp farming in fresh water areas nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The ban will take effect 120 days after Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai publicly ordered the enforcement of the ban in the Royal
Gazette, according to a government press release received
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While environmentalists have applauded the development,
anti-government critics have been giving new ammunition saying the
ban would send the shrimp farm industry reeling at a time when the
government is supposed to protect viable businesses.
</P>
<P>
The NEB resolution was based on Article 9 of the 1992
Environmental Protection Act which gives the prime minister
absolute authority to ban any activity which might cause
environmental hazards.
</P>
<P>
To shrimp farmers and companies selling shrimp feed, inland
shrimp farming is a bonanza of high profits. But as they moved
farming locations further inland, salt water has been transported
to fill their ponds, thus threatening paddy fields and eroding
soil.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have relentlessly crusaded against inland
shrimp farming.
</P>
<P>
The decision is expected to trigger a major outcry from farm
operators. But Science Minister Yingphan Manasikarn said that
although he sympathized with the shrimp farmers, he could not
allow the farming to continue because of its hazards to the
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
"I know it brings very high income to the country but if we
allow the farming to remain in our fresh water area, foreign
governments may boycott our other exports and we will suffer
more," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
