<HEADLINE> Thai Monk Hands Over 1.2 Million Dollars to Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A Buddhist monk has handed over to
the Thai government 1.2 million U.S. dollars and other donations
from worshippers to help rescue the ailing economy, government
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Phra Maha Bua Yanasampanno of Wat Pa Bantad in Udon Thani on
the outskirts of Bangkok has collected 182.5 kilograms of gold
ornaments, 12 million baht (300,000 dollars) and 1.2 million
dollars in cash since he began asking his followers for donations
to the government on April 12.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, thousands of people thronged his temple to hand
in their valuables and cash.
</P>
<P>
This was the first lot of U.S. dollars handed over to the
government, said Col. Therdsak Chaiyasith, a member of the "Help
the Country Project."
</P>
<P>
The rest of the cash will be handed over later, Therdsak said,
adding that he wanted to raise at least one ton of gold.
</P>
<P>
"The gold will be handed over to the central bank when the
amount is big enough," Therdsak said.
</P>
<P>
Central bank Governor Chatumongol Sonakul said the "Help the
Country Project" will inspire the Thais to join forces in pulling
the country out of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Every one should pray that the generous rich will donate their
assets to salvage the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has collapsed into a recession since the devaluation
of the baht on July 2 last year. Governmental and non-governmental
organizations have launched various campaigns to help resolve the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
