<HEADLINE> Belarus President Hopes to Maintain Military Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Belarus President Alexandr
Lukashenko said on Tuesday his country should keep its military
strength amid NATO's continued eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
As quoted by an Interfax news agency report from Minsk,
Lukashenko said to a group of graduates from the National Military
Academy that he advocated prudence in downsizing the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its expansion despite the opposition from other
countries, he said, NATO was exerting pressures on those unwilling
to follow the Western bloc's political and economic lines.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstance, both Russia and Belarus should keep
military strength strong enough for defending their territories,
and work together in restructuring their military forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bound by a Russia-Belarus Union from 1996, the two countries,
however, have decided to keep their armed forces independent.
</P>
<P>
Belarus, which joined the NATO's Partnership for Peace program
of military cooperation in January 1995, has planned to cut its
currently 80,000-strong military personnel down to 65,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
