<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Exploration of Coal-Bed Methane Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China is hoping to establish an
improved industrial system for coal-bed methane by the year 2010,
one capable of producing 10 billion cubic meters of coal-bed
methane annually.
</P>
<P>
China now has 35,000 billion cu m of coal-bed methane
resources, 62 percent of which lie buried in the country's
northern regions. This untapped coal-bed methane has a volume
equivalent to that of China's conventional natural gas resources,
placing China third in the world in this resource.
</P>
<P>
During the ninth Five-Year-Plan period (1996-2000), two or
three coal-bed methane production bases will be constructed to
step up exploration of the country's plentiful coal-bed methane.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by the year 2000 the gap between supply
and demand for petroleum will be 40 million tons and that of
natural gas will be between two billion to five billion cu m. And
the supply-to-demand gap for petroleum will grow from 70 million
to 80 million tons, and 20 billion cu m to 40 billion cu m for
natural gas by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the State Council, China United Coal-Bed Methane
Co. Ltd. (CUCBM) was set up in 1996 to handle all activities
related to exploration of coal-bed methane resources in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Central Government has drafted and published a wide
range of preferential policies to speed up growth of the coal-bed
methane industry.
</P>
<P>
China has succeeded in attracting foreign funds and
technologies for the exploration of coal-bed methane resources as
exploration demands high investment and involves great risks.
</P>
<P>
Provinces like Anhui, Liaoning and Shanxi have been given
approval to cooperate with foreign transnationals of the United
States and Australia in developing coal-bed methane resources.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, CUCBM signed a contract with Texaco of the
United States to jointly explore coal-bed methane resources under
2,600 sq km of land in east China's Anhui Province. This land is
thought to contain 60 billion cu m of coal-bed methane, and the
cooperation project will require an investment of 500 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
CUCBM also signed two separate contracts with the Atlantic
Richfield Company and the Phillips Petroleum Company of the United
States to develop coal-bed methane in 8,700 sq km of Hedong
Coal-Bed Methane Field in north China's Shanxi Province. This
cooperative prospecting project will involve an investment of 30
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hedong Coal-Bed Methane Field has an area of 16,000 sq km and
is estimated to contain 3,000 billion cu m of coal-bed methane
resources. By the year 2010 it will be able to produce five
billion cu m of coal-bed methane annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
