<HEADLINE> Primakov Stresses Russian-U.S. Cooperation on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Tuesday called for continuous Russian-U.S. joint
efforts to seek a political solution to the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told the Itar-Tass news agency that Joint moves by
Russia and the United States were of special importance prior to
the six-nation Contact Group's discussions on the Kosovo crisis in
Bonn, which is scheduled to start on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Together with U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, Russian Deputy
Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky visited Kosovo on Sunday and
held talks with Ibrahim Rugova, the Kosovo ethnic Albanian
leader. It was the first joint action taken by the two envoys over
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
During his trip, Afanasyevsky also exchanged views with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on seeking a political way
out of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Primakov hailed the Afanasyevsky's mission as a key effort to
help solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
A Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said Tuesday that
Afanasyevsky had called on the Serbian authorities and the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo to resume negotiations which, he noted, was
the first step toward ending the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted Afanasyevsky as saying that the Serbian
side "has been ready for negotiations" but the ethnic Albanian
leaders "have neither responded to the call, nor guaranteed a
ceasefire."
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, a Serbian province where 90 percent of the population
are ethnic Albanians, has sunk into chaos since February when the
illegal Kosovo Liberation Army clashed with Serb police. Several
hundred people have been killed in continuing conflicts.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Afanasyevsky would attend the Contact
Group meeting in Bonn and brief group members on his recent trip
to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group -- the United States, Russia, Britain,
Germany, France and Italy -- has an international mandate to
monitor events in the former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
