<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Elects Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, Tuesday ended a nearly two-month deadlock in finding a
new head by electing Alexandr Tkachenko as its speaker.
</P>
<P>
Tkachenko, 59, of the Peasants Party, finally won a 232-37 vote
after the unicameral legislative body had held over 20 rounds of
failed voting since May 12. Forty-five votes were declared invalid.
</P>
<P>
Under the Ukrainian Constitution, at least 226 votes, or half
those of the 450-seat legislature, were required to be elected.
</P>
<P>
After his election, Tkachenko, the previous Supreme Soviet's
first vice-chairman since May 1994, said his priorities were to
form a leading group and improve the parliament's legislative work.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the parliament and the government should have
better relations, he said the two sides should work together to
take long-waited measures to defuse the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tkachenko was the former Soviet republic's agriculture and food
minister before 1991. He briefly served as Ukraine's agriculture
minister in 1992, and co-founded the Land and People agrarian
association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Attract More Tourists From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is planning to organize more
travel shows in other neighboring countries, especially Thailand,
to attract tourists from there following its tourism promotion
campaign launched in Singapore recently.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's first two-day travel show in Singapore has brought
about initiation of tour arrangements for more Singaporeans and
tourists to visit the country, the official New Light of Myanmar
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among Myanmar's neighboring countries, Thailand plays a key
role in supplying tourists to the countries, ranking second after
Japan.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year that ended in March, more than 7,000
tourists from Thailand visited Myanmar out of more than 246,000
from 24 countries and regions, according to the official monthly
Economic Indicators.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the entry point of Yangon International Airport,
Myanmar has also drawn visitors through border points, receiving a
large number of visitors through Kawthaung at the southern end of
Myanmar bordering Thailand, where some islands are opened to
foreign investors for building resorts.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's investment in Myanmar's hotels and tourism sector,
second only to Singapore, amounted to 200 million U.S. dollars in
eight projects at the end of March this year, compared to a total
foreign investment of more than 1 billion dollars in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Despite its "Visit Myanmar Year" campaign launched in 1996,
Myanmar has received a smaller number of tourists in the past two
years. The country is taking measures to attract tourists in the
forthcoming open tourist season beginning October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
