<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Customs Boss Sentenced for Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A former Argentine customs
leader was sentenced to 10 years in jail on a charge of
"aggravated smuggling," Argentine judicial sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Judge Guillermo Tiscornia said Juan Carlos Delconte, former
head of the Argentine National Customs Administration in
1984-1989, had caused "a multimillion damage" to the country.
</P>
<P>
The judge said Delconte created a "parallel register" in the
Ezeiza international airport to smuggle goods in the name of
non-existent individuals, or historical figures.
</P>
<P>
The former official undertook the smuggling along with two
accomplices who operated in the airport and were in charge of
securing the clandestine trading, Tiscornia said.
</P>
<P>
Delconte began smuggling in 1991 and subsequently served four
years in prison, but was set free in September 1994 on bail of
150,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
