<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea Fish Species Affected By Sri Lankan Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Some sea fish species have been
adversely affected by a recent oil spill off Sri Lanka's Colombo
harbor, the official Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report by the National Aquatic Resources Research and
Development Agency on the environmental impact of the spill said
there was still light crude oil spread over the surface of the
shore area.
</P>
<P>
Last week, more than 70 tons of crude oil were leaked into the
sea during unloading from an Iranian tanker five miles off the
Colombo port, causing a thick oil slick along the coast extending
about seven miles.
</P>
<P>
The oil made it difficult for some species of fish to move
especially near coral reefs and rocks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said if the oil gets deposited in the sea bed the
situation would be even worse. The impact of the oil spill on sea
birds is also being studied, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There had been no report of fish deaths in large numbers yet,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that damage to the environment caused by
the oil spill was estimated at 100,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
