<HEADLINE> Bangkok Police to Enforce Ban on Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Police in Bangkok are to get tough
with people who smoke in public places in violation of tobacco
control laws, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The police will enforce the Non-Smokers' Health Protection Act
and the Tobacco Products Control Act.
</P>
<P>
Fines of 2,000 baht (50 U.S. dollars) will be imposed on people
who smoke in places such as malls, supermarkets, barber shops,
tailor shops, beauty salons, drugstores and state offices and on
buses.
</P>
<P>
The police will also check air-conditioned restaurants.
Restaurateurs who have not set aside smoking areas will be liable
to fines of 20,000 baht (500 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
