<HEADLINE> Brazilians Go Wild after Winning from Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian soccer fans
went absolutely wild on Tuesday after their team won a tense and
hard-fought World Cup semi-final against the Netherlands, 4-2 on
penalties.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the defending World Cup champions burst into
spontaneous street parties and horn-honking traffic jams while
firecrackers boomed across the country after goalkeeper Taffarel
saved a second penalty to put Brazil into World Cup final on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Fans ran, hands outstretched, down the beachfront streets of
Brazil's famous carnival city of Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
Moments before, all eyes glued to televisions and screens set
up in bars, offices and on street corners around the city, as they
watched in breathless silence.
</P>
<P>
In Sao Paulo, the biggest city of the country, Brazilians
shouting "Five-time champions" and waving banners hung out of cars
careening down the wide Paulista Avenue, while another part of the
street was blocked off and filled with hundreds of thousands of
celebrating inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Most radio and television commentators predicted that if Brazil
played at the same level, they would probably defeat the winner of
the France-Croatia semi-final to take fifth World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
Emotion even overtook the usually sedate capital city of
Brasilia, where there were at least two major automobile pileups
as residents raced madly home.
</P>
<P>
A soccer fan, a longtime foreign resident here, said after
Brazil winning over the Netherlands that "That's the real Brazil
playing."  
</P>
</TEXT>
