<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Keen to Expand Trade Relations with Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government is keen
to expand its trade ties with European Union (EU) countries,
Foreign Trade Minister Samuel Guzowski said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, Guzowski said, Costa Rica hoped that the
EU's preferential system for Central American agricultural
products could be extended to the region's industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Europe, next only to the United States, is the second largest
overseas market for Costa Rica, which exports mainly its coffee,
banana, fruits and ornamental plants there.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's banana takes a 25 percent share in the European
market.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, its exports to Europe totaled 847 million U.S.
dollars, up 0.7 percent from the previous year and nearly double
over the 1990 figure of 430 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Guzowski said, the government would like to
attract more European capital into the country, especially in
areas involving latest technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
