<HEADLINE> Thailand's Energy Consumption Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's energy consumption in
the form of oil and gas fell by nearly 8 percent in the first five
months of this year compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Total petroleum demand excluding consumption by petrochemical
industries, dropped by 7.9 percent to the equivalent of 879,820
barrels of oil per day, according to figures from the Petroleum
Authority of Thailand available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of refined products fell by 10.9 percent to 674,290
barrels a day with virtually all categories dropping. Diesel oil
use declined by 16.9 percent to 273,130 barrels, duel oil was down
10.7 percent to 143,210 barrels and gasoline down 4.8 percent to
59,940 barrels.
</P>
<P>
But consumption of natural gas in lieu of fuel oil rose 3.4
percent to 205,530 barrels, spurred by the rise in the power
generation and industrial sectors, which grew by 2.1 percent and
10.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In line with the drop in consumption, procurement of petroleum
dipped by 10.8 percent to 1,011,490 barrels per day. Total imports
slipped by 14.4 percent to 697,890 barrels, including 675,210
barrels of crude and 22,680 barrels of finished products.
</P>
<P>
Total supplies of indigenous petroleum declined 1.5 percent to
313,600 barrels per day, consisting of 250,200 barrels of natural
gas (down 1.2 percent), 43,200 barrels of condensate (up 0.9
percent) and 29,200 barrels of crude oil (down 9 percent).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbying Cost Reached 1.17 Billion Dollars in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Special interests in the United
States reported spending 1.17 billion dollars last year to lobby
Congress, the White House and the federal bureaucracy, according
to the first computerized study of year-end disclosure reports.
</P>
<P>
In all, companies, labor unions, interest groups and
municipalities reported hiring 14,484 lobbyists, a contingent that
outnumbers members of Congress 27-to-1, according to an Associated
Press computer analysis of lobbying disclosure reports.
</P>
<P>
The database, a joint project with the nonprofit, nonpartisan
Center for Responsive Politics, provides the most comprehensive
look at lobbying spending since federal disclosures began two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The most heavily lobbied issues in 1997 were the federal
budget, taxes, health, transportation and defense, the analysis
showed.
</P>
<P>
About 42 percent of the lobbyists listed the budget as one of
their interest areas.
</P>
<P>
The king of the lobbying crowd in 1997 was the American Medical
Association, which reported spending 17.1 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The nation's doctor lobby is pressing to give patients and
doctors more freedom under managed care health plans, and for
legislation to reduce teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
Also lobbying on anti-smoking legislation was tobacco, beer and
food giant Philip Morris, the second-biggest spender at 15.8
million dollars. Part of that was spent trying to persuade
Congress to ratify a 368 billion-dollar deal between the tobacco
industry and a group of state attorneys generals. After the deal
was altered to add a 1.10 dollar-per-pack tax that the tobacco
companies opposed, the Senate shelved it last month.
</P>
<P>
Overall, major tobacco industry players reported spending 31.65
million dollars lobbying last year.
</P>
<P>
But that was only about half as much as the telecommunications
industry, which spent 63.96 million dollars. In that industry,
several giants are seeking approval for mergers, and local
telephone companies and long distance companies are pressing to
break into each other's markets.
</P>
<P>
Other major categories included the pharmaceutical industry,
oil and gas, defense, the automobile industry and business
groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Laid-off Workers Find Jobs in Consumer Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Chinese
workers laid off from manufacturing industries now find jobs in
consumer industries.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Liping, who lost job at a textile mill in Taiyuan,
capital of Shanxi Province, finds herself a place at free market
selling clothing every day and earns 4 to 5 times more than the
salary she used to earn from the mill. This is nothing
extraordinary in Taiyuan, where 24,000 unemployed workers have
relocate positions in free markets.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has spent 170 million yuan (20.5
million US dollars) investing in 181 free markets, opening up
channels to absorb more laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Some debt-ridden state-owned enterprises are also setting up
markets in their idle workshops or warehouses to provide jobs for
redundant workers.
</P>
<P>
The Taiyuan Leather Shoe Factory, for instance, turned some of
its workshops into a large market where some 360 workers have jobs
again. The market earned a profit of 1.7 million yuan and paid the
local government 1.8 million yuan in tax last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
