<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Presents Credentials to Kuchma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The new Chinese Ambassador to Ukraine,
Zhou Xiaopei, presented his credentials to Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, the third Chinese ambassador to Ukraine, told Kuchma that
China will continue to support Ukraine's efforts in maintaining
its independence, sovereignty and dignity.
</P>
<P>
He said China and Ukraine have built up a sound relationship of
mutual trust, mutual benefit and mutual support since the two
countries established diplomatic ties in January 1992.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said it is important for Ukraine to develop a special
partnership with China. He said he is happy about the development
of bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
While thanking China for supporting Ukraine's efforts in
maintaining independence and territorial integrity, Kuchma said
Ukraine backs China's stand on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Ukrainian government will stick to the
"one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Zhou briefed Kuchma over the recent visit U.S. President Bill
Clinton made to China and the Ukrainian president welcomed the
improvement of the Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that as two big countries and permanent members of
the United Nations Security Council, China and the United States
should be friendly, not hostile, to each other.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, Kuchma said that Ukraine would join
hands with China to further relations between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
