<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Invest More in Tianjin's Agriculture, Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment in north
China's biggest port city, Tianjin, remains stable although more
rises are registered in agriculture and infrastructure and
downfalls in real restate, according to the Deputy Mayor Wang
Shuzu.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that during the first five months, contracted foreign
investment in agriculture rose by 150 percent over the same 1997
period while that in real estate dropped by 67 percent. Investment
in infrastructure, especially in road communications facilities,
rose considerably to take up 35 percent of the total investment
and reach the level of the conventioanl manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
There is also an increasing number of larger projects, the
deputy mayor said. Forty-six projects, each involving 5 million
U.S. dollars or above, were approved in the first five months, up
50 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the Asian financial crisis, investment from Japan, the
Republic of Korea and Southeast Asian countries dropped sharply,
but investment from the United States and Europe shot up, he said,
adding that in the first five months, the U.S. investment alone
more than doubled that of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Shuzu, from January through May, 378
foreign-funded enterprise were approved, a slight rise over the
same period last year. The amount of foreign investment totalled
804 million U.S. dollars, about the same level of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to local statistics, foreign-funded enterprises which
have been operating in this city added 320 million U.S. dollars of
investment from January through May, which indicates the
successful operation of these enterprises and their confidence in
investing in China, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the municipal government plans to adopt a series
of new measures to further improve the environment for foreign
investment. 
</P>
