<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Shell Dike Preserved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Huanghua City of Northern Hebei
Province is pulling out all the stops to save the only large-scale
ancient shell dike on the Pacific-Ocean's western shores,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
It said that only one kilometer of the 31-kilometer
Huanghua-Haixing Ancient Shell Dike has survived people's
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The dike consists of six separate parts parallel to the area's
modern coastline. It was gradually formed in the past 7,000 years
as tides and winds pushed shells onto land.
</P>
<P>
The dike is one of the world's three longest and oldest shell
dikes -- the other two are located in North America and South
America's Surinam. The Huanghua dike records important information
on environmental changes on the Bohai Sea's west shore.
</P>
<P>
The information is very important for calculating future
geological changes and setting a long-term development strategy
for the area, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chaoying, a Tianjin deputy to the National People's
Congress, submitted a proposal in 1995 pleading for immediate
protection of the dike.
</P>
<P>
On August 10, 1995, local government officially banned mining
of the dike.
</P>
<P>
Du Likai, director of the Huanghua County-Level Ancient Shell
Dike Protection Zone, and his two colleagues now go there twice a
day to make sure no one has dug the dike, chopped down trees or
dumped rubbish there.
</P>
<P>
Although "scars" are still obvious on the dike, grass and trees
are gradually covering them. Fences now keep cars and people from
the dike, and dike guardians have their own watch station so they
do not freeze at night.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is now well in the process of establishing a provincial
protection zone for the dike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
