<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Mount Merapi Shows Signs of Eruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Residents around Indonesia's most
active volcano have been on alert after deadly Mount Merapi showed
signs of a possible eruption, the Indonesian Observer reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Merapi's status had been raised from "normal" to "alert," said
Mas Atje Purbawinata, head of the directorate of Volcanology in
Yogyakarta in Central Java Province.
</P>
<P>
He said the alarm was raised after a rise in volcanic activity
had caused a large amount of magma moving closer to the top of the
2,968-meter-high mountain.
</P>
<P>
"The endless supply (of magma) will cause an accumulation of
volcanic material on the surface which can turn into hot gas and
ash," he said.
</P>
<P>
The volcano is about 20 kilometers from Yogyakarta and forms a
backdrop of the historical city of two million people.
</P>
<P>
In November 1994, Mount Merapi, 400 kilometers east of Jakarta,
erupted without warning and killed 60 people. In January 1997,
more than 8,000 nearby villagers had to be evacuated after the
volcano spewed hot gas, ash and lava. 
</P>
</TEXT>
