<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stopping Marine Environmental Degradation In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Deterioration of the marine
environment near the port city of Tianjin, about 100 km east of
Beijing, has been checked, according to Cui Yucheng, deputy
director of the Tianjin Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The discharge of pollutants has been reduced, with inorganic
nitrogen discharges down to 89.4 percent from 99.5 percent in
1995; inorganic phosphorus from 78 percent to 63 percent; oil
pollutants from 63 percent to 57 percent, and COD from 13.6
percent to zero.
</P>
<P>
However, marine environment experts say that the ocean
pollution situation is still serious around the Dagukou and
Beitangkou river outlets.
</P>
<P>
The sea near Tianjin, near the lower end of Bohai Bay, covers
an area of 3,000-sq.km., into which the city discharges about 500
million tons of waste water each year, and marine oil exploration
and transportation make the situation worse.
</P>
<P>
The city has built three waste water treatment plants to handle
more than 40 percent of the city's waste water, and industrial
pollution has been reduced since the city closed a large number of
polluting enterprises. More than 80 percent of the city's
industrial waste water is treated and over 65 percent is up to
discharge standards, Cui told reporters.
</P>
<P>
All new enterprises have been told that they need to be
equipped with environmental protection facilities in the 1990s,
and the city will close all other polluters that don't meet
standards by next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
