<HEADLINE> White House: Closer Military Contacts With China on Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Closer military-to-military
contacts between the United States and China are "coming on line,"
said White House Spokesman Michael McCurry on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The development, McCurry told a press briefing here, is part of
the efforts to establish U.S.-China strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
When Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited the United States
last October, the idea was discussed and "some of those things are
coming on line now," said the spokesman, who accompanied
U.S. President Bill Clinton in his recent visit to China.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the two countries have agreed to hold the first
annual meeting of the Military Maritime Consultative Agreement
Forum later this month, so as to promote safety in naval and air
operations and avoid incidents at sea.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they have agreed to carry out search and rescue
operations together and exchange military observers to observe
military exercises on a reciprocal basis.
</P>
<P>
Military officials are also going to work on how the two sides
could work to de-conflict operations if they are responding to
some kind of national disaster.
</P>
<P>
"The exchange of senior military observers and military visits
have served the purpose of helping both our sides understand
better the ways in which their militaries operate and project
force in a very sensitive region," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that closer military-to-military contact "has the
benefit of reducing tensions, of helping people understand better
what the military strategies of both sides are."
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Pentagon Spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon confirmed
that the United States and China have been working on ways to
improve military-to-military relationships since December 1996,
when Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian visited Washington. The
theme was discussed many times between the two sides later on.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the two countries had joint search-and-rescue air
exercises out of Hong Kong last December and a same exercise is
scheduled for this December involving the Hong Kong Civil Aviation
Department, the U.S. Air Force and the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton flew back home last weekend from a nine-day
visit to China, where an agreement was reached on reciprocal
observer missions watching joint exercises in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Over the next weeks and months, Bacon said, representatives
from China and the United States will sit down to work out a
schedule in this respect.
</P>
<P>
He called the move "new and a breakthrough," and actually "a
rather important confidence-building measure."
</P>
<P>
At the U.S. State Department, Spokesman James Rubin commented
Tuesday that both on humanitarian grounds and in terms of
preventing unwanted risks and miscalculation, "these kind of
greater military-to-military contacts are of benefit both to the
security of the United States and to the Chinese as well."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
