<HEADLINE> Sichuan Accelerates Communications Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The central government and Sichuan
provincial government plan to earmark billions of yuan over the
next few years to develop transportation infrastructure in the
southwest China province.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Provincial Governor Zou Guangyan said that the state will
invest more than 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US dollars) in
railway construction between 1996-2000. And railways stretching
347 km have been added in the last two years alone.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Sichuan will spend additional 4.15 billion yuan (500
million US dollars) to accelerate four railway projects, including
the multi-track railway from the city of Baoji to Chengdu, the
provincial capital of Sichuan, and the Chengdu-Kunming and
Chongqing-Daxian electrified railways. The railways are planned to
enter operations in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Plans through the year 2000 call for Sichuan to build new
expressways stretching 1,000 km. Recent reports indicate that
Sichuan has completed expressways covering 341 km in the past two
years, and the provincial government plans to allocate some 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) for related construction
during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among other communications projects on the provincial
government agenda are an expansion project of Shuangliu Airport to
accommodate Boeing 747 with an annual flow of 13 million
passengers and construction of Mianyang, Jiuzhai and Huanglong
airports.  
</P>
