<HEADLINE> Guangzhou to Allow Private Sector to Conduct Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The city government of Guangzhou
in south China's Guangdong Province adopted a resolution on Monday
allowing the private sector to conduct foreign trade and economic
cooperative activities.
</P>
<P>
This is the country's first official effort to encourage the
sector to get involved in a field long dominated by state-owned
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses will be able to set up joint ventures with
overseas investors, and related government departments should
provide necessary services, according to the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Private firms can conduct foreign trade independently after
approval, and are entitled to open branches abroad and launch
projects.
</P>
<P>
Those private companies that have the status of "legal person"
will receive the same favorable policies as state-owned
enterprises in conducting processing business supplied by foreign
partners.
</P>
<P>
The city also will organize trade inspection groups for the
sector to participate in world trade fairs and also provide
training for them, the resolution said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
