<HEADLINE> Beijing Further Strengthens Emission Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Spots checks on vehicles in the
Chinese capital are helping to make the air a little easier to
breathe, China Daily said today.
</P>
<P>
In the three months from April 1 to the end of June, roadside
checks were carried out on more than 17,000 automobiles and 55
percent of them needed to have catalytic converters installed.
</P>
<P>
The spot checks are aimed at encouraging car drivers to keep up
maintenance of their vehicles to reduce exhaust emissions.
</P>
<P>
Li Tiejun, an official with the Beijing Environmental
Protection Bureau, disclosed that the percentage points of
automobiles reaching state standards in tail-gas emissions had
climbed gradually since the beginning of the check, possibly
because some car drivers were taking measures to maintain their
cars better.
</P>
<P>
The municipal environmental protection bureau has set up four
mobile inspection teams in Beijing's eight urban districts to
carry out daily spot checks on tail-gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that the spot checks and the installation of
catalytic converters were just end-of-pipe control measures. A
significant improvement in tail-gas emissions could only be
achieved during the car-manufacturing process.
</P>
<P>
In a tail-gas sampling survey of ten different models of new
cars, Beijing's environmental protection bureau found that only
Red Flag, Cherokee and Audi cars met all the state standards.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 80 percent of the lead in the capital
city's air, 63 percent of tis carbon monoxide and 37 percent of
its nitrogen oxide come from tail gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
