<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Organized to Solve Their Own Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Chinese
farmers are no longer worried about selling their crops now that
farmers' associations are there to help them solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Weizhuang Township of Chengxian County in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, for example, are eagerly awaiting their
apple harvest because a local fruit association has guaranteed the
sales.
</P>
<P>
Years ago, local growers called their fruit "bitter apples"
because of marketing problems. Later, they organized among
themselves a farmers' fruit association to take charge of product
sales.
</P>
<P>
Now, the association has organized a marketing force of more
than 50 people, and established some information networks and
sales outlets in coastal areas and other parts of the country. So,
what is left for farmers is to take good care of their fruit.
</P>
<P>
As a result, farmers now call their fruit "golden apples," and
the association is widely accepted and trusted as it also provides
other services and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
The Fruits Growers' Association in Fengxiang County has opened
16 branches in villages as well as more than 50 sales outlets
elsewhere. By now, it has sold more than 30 million kilograms of
apples for farmers.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas of Qingdao in Shandong Province, east China,
farmers have formed 1,749 associations involving more than 70,000
members. While in Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, herdsmen also
joined the effort, and set up some 1,000 technical associations.
</P>
<P>
Such associations in Yanshi in Henan Province have gone so far
as to send farmers to the local agricultural university for
training or to invite experts to give lectures and
guidance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Custom Tries Quicker Clearance With New System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- EAS International Transportation
Ltd, an established Chinese cargo shipper, announced yesterday
that it will use a high-tech computer network to process customs
claims at its Beijing center.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Wang Beipei, EAS general manager as
saying that "the establishment of the center will redue operation
costs and increase efficiency for both our company and our clients.
</P>
<P>
The computer network, the first international cargo forwarder
to ever get approval from Beijing Customs to launch such a
facility, which links customs, banks, airlines, cargo owners.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be far more advanced and streamlined than
traditional handing customs declaration and taxation by hand.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the EAS operates transportation business in 98
cities at home and 120 nations and regions overseas.
</P>
<P>
Wang Junyin, deputy director of Beijing Customs, said "we plan
to increase the proportion of computerized customs clearances to
total documents for import and export managed to up to 50 percent."
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Beijing Customs has started a pilot project using
the advanced system to handle customs clearance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
