<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Find Philippines Attractive:Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines continues to be
attractive to foreign investors despite the ill-effects of the
ongoing regional financial crisis, Business World said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, quoting a survey conducted among 84 chief
executive officers of multinational corporations based in the
country, said the Philippines was regarded as the third most
politically stable country next to Australia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Most of the respondents believed that President Joseph Estrada
was sincere in his efforts to strengthen the economy despite the
ongoing Asian financial crisis, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investors also believed that Estrada would continue
the economic policies and reforms initiated by his predecessor,
former president Fidel Ramos, but he would only be "partially
successful" in implementing these policies and reforms.
</P>
<P>
The challenge for the administration lies on its ability and
commitment to not only sustain the momentum of reform the Ramos
administration has started, but also ensure its proper
implementation, said Peter Wallace who made the survey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wallace noted that the international community
continued to see the Philippines as the least affected by the
regional financial crisis and lauded the measures the country took
to handle the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
