<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Slow in Using Legal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's ordinary workers are slow in
using legal means to protect their rights compared with business
people, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
While most law firms dealing with commercial cases enjoy good
business, few handle exclusively labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
One major reason is that most workers involved in labor disputes
are simply unaware of legal protection and turning to law firms
for help, according to Han Zhili, of Beijing Labor Dispute
Arbitration Committee.
</P>
<P>
A lot of them ask elementary questions such as "What is listed
in the Labor Law?" on a new labor dispute hot line opened by Han's
committee.
</P>
<P>
The line has been busy since the number -- 26677160 -- was made
public in recent TV programs. More than 200 people called over the
weekend, which was the fourth anniversary of the passing of the
law.
</P>
<P>
But, Han is quoted as saying, many people rang only to find
that the period during which litigation was allowed had expired.
</P>
<P>
According to Han, people have been accustomed to talking their
disputes over with their employers and superiors instead of paying
some thousand yuan for a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Justice show that since China
restored its system of lawyers in 1979, the country has about
8,400 law firms with over 100,000 lawyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges U.S. to Ease Cuba Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Vice Chairman Sir Leon Brittan
of the European Union Commission said on Tuesday that the U.S.
Congress should approve a legislation to ease U.S. sanctions on
foreign companies doing business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club here, Brittan said that if
the U.S. Congress eased restrictions, the 15-nation European Union
(EU) would avoid investing in companies holding assets that
include U.S. property seized by the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
The EU made the obligation under an agreement, which was
reached last May with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the U.S. would grant European companies
permanent waivers to the Helms-Burton law while the EU agreed to
join in creating a global registry of property confiscated by Cuba
and other governments that would remain off-limits to investors.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law, which was proposed by Sen. Jesse Helms
and Rep. Dan Burton, needs to be amended to guarantee the waivers
for the EU. But the prospect appears to be slim.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. Congress did not act, "the pressure would be
enormous" to return the dispute to the World Trade Organization
(WT), said Brittan.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans suspended their action before the WTO in the
spring of 1997 to allow time for negotiations with the
administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
