<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian Senator Michel Cogger was fined Tuesday
3,000 Canadian dollars (2,040 U.S. dollars) after he was convicted
last month for influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
He was also put on 12 months' probation and order to do
community service for 120 hours, reports said.
(Canada-Senator-Fine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Hundreds of Protestant Orangemen paraded in central
Belfast as disturbances and protests continued across Northern
Ireland on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
By early Tuesday evening police reported widespread road
blocking, some vehicle hijackings and stone throwing by
pro-British loyalist gangs. (UK-N.Ireland-Violence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Tuesday that it
regretted a vote by the U.N. General Assembly to upgrade the
status of the Palestinian U.N. representation.
</P>
<P>
"We regret this decision. We think this was a mistake. We think
that this decision undermines the chances of bringing peace to the
Middle East," State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a
regular briefing. (US-Palestinians-U.N. Vote)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos warned
on Tuesday that threats of military intervention in the Serbian
province of Kosovo by the West are encouraging secession with
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos, who is on a visit to the United States, told a
press conference here that Greece would oppose the union or
secession of Kosovo with Albanian, saying it would be
"intolerable." (US-Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran said Tuesday that it would not recognize any
bilateral agreement to divide the Caspian Sea into national
sectors for exploiting its resources, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi was quoted as
saying that a legal regime on the Caspian should be determined by
all of the five littoral states, and Iran would not accept any
bilateral agreement that is not in the interests of all.
(Iran-Caspian)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The General Assembly of the United Nations
Tuesday adopted a resolution which upgraded the status of the
Palestinian U.N. observer delegation.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted with 124 votes for, four against and
10 abstentions. The United States, Israel, Micronesia and the
Marshall Islands voted against the resolution.
(UN-Palestine-Resolution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel will visit Moscow
this Saturday to meet his Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov for
consultations mainly on the current situation in Kosovo, the
German Foreign Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before his Moscow trip, Kinkel would visit Albania and the
Republic of Macedonia Wednesday and Thursday also for talks on the
conflict in the Serbian province which borders the two countries.
(Germany-Russia-Kosovo) 
