Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress, visited a village near the city of
Siping in Jilin Province today to discuss with local farmers the
way of electing village committees.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday morning, he went to the village of Huojiadian, with a
population of 2,945, where four village committee elections have
been held since 1988 in accordance with the Organic Village
Committee Law.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met yesterday with a
delegation from the International University Sports Federation
(FISU) led by its first vice-president George Killian.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Jia Qinglin of Beijing municipality was among those
present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing yesterday told visiting
Mexico's Secretary of Foreign Relations Rosario Green Macias that
China is ready to work with Mexico to establish a bilateral
relationship of comprehensive cooperation into the next century.
</P>
<P>
China has always attached importance to its ties with Mexico
and holds that the growth of Sino-Mexican ties would serve the
interests of the two nations as well as the world peace and
development, Li said.
</P>
<P>
-- Wei Jianxing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China Central
Committee, recently said China's public construction project
contracts must open to bidding across the country.
</P>
<P>
Wei made the remarks at a national construction meeting July 6
and 7 in east China's Jiangsu Province, where he said that all
construction projects, except those involving national security
and disaster relief will need to be opened to public bidding as a
matter of openness, fairness, and equal competition. The move is
meant to prevent corruption and to ensure efficiency and quality.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Oblivious to the sweltering temperature in the classroom,
candidates in China's national college entrance examinations had
but one aim in mind -- obtaining a high enough mark to get into
the university of their choice.
</P>
<P>
This year, as in previous years, the examinations are being
held over three days. The only difference is that his year the
number of candidates has hit a record 3.2 million -- 340,000 more
than last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Environmental protection will be major feature of China's
tourism program in 1999, according to the China National Tourism
Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
The CNTA will co-operate with the State Environmental
Protection Administration and other departments to make ecology
the main attraction of its tourism promotion drive for 1999.
</P>
