<HEADLINE> Canadian Hockey Czar Freed after Six Months in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada's disgraced hockey czar Alan
Eagleson came out of jail Tuesday on parole six months into an
18-month sentence for fraud.
</P>
<P>
Eagleson, 65, walked out of a correction center west of Toronto
early Tuesday morning and didn't make any comments before driving
away, reports said.
</P>
<P>
As a condition of his release, Eagleson will have to report to
a probation officer for 12 months, and is forbidden to leave the
province he is living during that year.
</P>
<P>
A former player agent and founder of the NHL Players'
Association, Eagleson pleaded guilty in Boston, the United States,
on January 6 to three counts of fraud and theft. He was fined one
million Canadian dollars (680,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On January 7, he also pleaded guilty to three counts of fraud
in the Canadian city of Toronto and agreed to an 18-month jail
term.
</P>
<P>
Eagleson has since been stripped of both his order of Canada
honor and membership in Canada's Sports Hall of Frame. He also
resigned from the country's Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
For the last two months, he has been on day parole working in a
sheet metal factory.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to continue working there for the next three to
six months, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Senator Fined for Influence-Peddling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Senator Michel Cogger was
fined Tuesday 3,000 Canadian dollars (2,040 U.S. dollars) after he
was convicted last month for influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
He was also put on 12 months' probation and order to do
community service for 120 hours, reports said.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still unclear whether Cogger will be stripped of
his status in the upper chamber of the Canadian parliament.
</P>
<P>
Cogger was convicted of lobbying government for a private
client for two years after he was named to the Senate in May,
1986, by then Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
</P>
<P>
His client, businessman Guy Montpetit, was reported to have
paid him 212,000 dollars in an unsuccessful bid for a
45-million-dollar government subsidy.
</P>
<P>
The client was convicted two months ago of buying Cogger's
influence, got a suspended sentence and was order to do 240 hours
of community work.
</P>
<P>
On his first trial in 1993, Cogger was acquitted on the grounds
he had no criminal intent.
</P>
<P>
But the Supreme Court of Canada ruled last year that the
senator must face a new trial.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frankfurt, London Stock Exchanges Forge Strategic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The two most important European stock
exchanges, the London Stock Exchange and Frankfurt's Deutsche
Boerse announced Tuesday that they have agreed to form a strategic
alliance in a bid to create a pan-European stock market.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, the two exchanges, which have been arch-rivals
for years, had agreed to establish a joint venture company with
equal holdings, the two companies said in a joint statement issued
Tuesday in London.
</P>
<P>
They also said that the alliance would be open for
participation of other stock exchanges, with the ultimate goal to
create a single European stock market based on a common electronic
trading platform.  
</P>
</TEXT>
