<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Night of Violence in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Protestant Orangemen
paraded in central Belfast as disturbances and protests continued
across Northern Ireland on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
By early Tuesday evening police reported widespread road
blocking, some vehicle hijackings and stone throwing by
pro-British loyalist gangs.
</P>
<P>
A bus was hijacked and set on fire in Belfast's Donegal Road
and cars burnt in North Queen Street.
</P>
<P>
In the most serious incident, a bomb was thrown at a police
patrol in Carrickfergus in County Antrim, but there were no
injuries.
</P>
<P>
The riots across the divided province were touched off by the
banning of Orangemen from parading on Sunday through a Roman
Catholic part of Portadown. The marchers, however, continued their
parade in defiance of the ruling of the independent Parades
Commission. More than 40 police have been injured over the last
three days.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to bolster the political process, Prime Minister Tony
Blair agreed on Tuesday to meet leaders of the Orange Order on
Thursday but said the parade ban was not open for discussion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
