<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Advance into Final with Penalty Shoot-out Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MARSEILLE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Brazil
advanced into the final after penalty shoot-out in a semi-final
match here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two teams played to a 1-1 draw after 90-minute regulation
time and failed to produce a golden goal in the extra time.
</P>
<P>
In the penalty shoot-out, the Brazilian team proved they were
better technically as they converted all their first four shots.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Brazilian goal-keeper Taffarel also proved
he was definitely among the best goal-keepers in the world as he
punched out the shots by Phillip Cocu and Ronald de Boer.
</P>
<P>
It is the second match decided by penalty shoot-out. The first
one was between England and Argentina in the second round which was
won by Argentina.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the match, the Dutch team took an upper
hand as they dominated the midfield and produced handful of scoring
chances.
</P>
<P>
But Patrick Kluivert failed to grasp any of the chances as he
time and again headed the ball over the cross-bar.
</P>
<P>
After a 0-0 first half, the Dutch team suffered a blow only 21
seconds into the second half when Ronaldo scored with his first
attempt to put Brazil 1-0 ahead.
</P>
<P>
But the Dutch team refused to give up and they finally hit in
the equaliser at the 87th minute through a header from Kluivert.
</P>
<P>
The extra-time was more exciting than the regulation time as
Ronaldo suddenly found his form and beat the Dutch defence line
several times.
</P>
<P>
But Edwin van der Sar, the Dutch goal-keeper, came to his team's
rescue and punched out Ronaldo's shots and took the match into
penalty shoot-out.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians are a better and luckier team in the penalty
shoot-out and that means they are just one match away from their
fifth World Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will play the final against the winners of another
semi-final match between Croatia and hosts France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980708.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unhappy over U.N. Upgrading Palestinian Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it regretted a vote by the U.N. General Assembly to
upgrade the status of the Palestinian U.N. representation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, the General Assembly voted overwhelmingly
to upgrade the Palestinian observer mission to a new, unique
status of a non-voting member in the 185-member assembly.
</P>
<P>
"We regret this decision. We think this was a mistake. We
think that this decision undermines the chances of bringing
peace to the Middle East," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"This is a unilateral action that we believe was unnecessary
and untimely, not to mention the precedent we think it
unfortunately set for those in the observer category at the
United Nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The vote on the resolution was 124 to four which include the
United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States was disappointed that only four
countries opposed the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
He said supporters of the move "didn't understand the fact
that the way to make peace in the Middle East is to promote
dialogue between the two parties and not to pursue symbolic
steps that may feel good but do not do good."
</P>
<P>
Nasser al-Kidwa, the Palestinian U.N. observer, said the vote
"makes us feel proud, strengthens our convictions of the justice
of our cause and increases our confidence that right could still
be achieved in our contemporary world."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
