<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls Against yen, Rises Against Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the
yen Tuesday in New York as news reports indicated that Japanese
leaders would get on a permanent tax cut.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports showed mixed messages about possible tax cuts
in the economically ailing country.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 138.75
Japanese yen, down from 140.15 late Monday. It was also changing
hands at 1.8145 German marks, up from 1.8124.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose against the German mark partly because traders
were buying yen and unloading both dollars and marks.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.5267 Swiss francs, up from 1.5240; 6.0816 French
francs, up from 6.0755; 1,787.20 Italian lire, up from 1,785.45;
and 1.4729 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4728.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6375 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6383 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
