<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Voices Sadness over Death of Nigerian Politician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government Tuesday
expressed deep sadness over the sudden death of prominent Nigerian
politician Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement issued
Tuesday evening: "We are deeply saddened by the news that Chief
Abiola has died. We extend our deepest sympathy to his family and
to the people of Nigeria at this time."
</P>
<P>
Abiola, declared himself president of Nigeria in the 1993
Nigerian elections and was latered detained, died of a heart
attack early Tuesday in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Chief Abiola had become the symbol of democracy in Nigeria. It
is therefore particularly tragic he should die now at this time of
change and hope in Nigeria," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Office Minister Tony Lloyd appealed
to the Nigerian government to conduct "free and fair elections" as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that if something good can come out of an
individual's death that this death should unite Nigerians around
the need to find common solutions and the demand for democratic
transformation," Lloyd said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
